{"title_page": "Jean Barker, Baroness Trumpington", "text_new": "{{redirect|Jean Barker|the film editor|Jean Barker (film editor)}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2013}}\n{{EngvarB|date=September 2019}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|honorific-prefix = [[The Right Honourable]]\n|name             = The Baroness Trumpington\n|honorific-suffix = [[Royal Victorian Order|DCVO]] [[Her Majesty's Most Honourable Privy Council|PC]]\n|image            = Baroness Trumpington 2011.jpg\n|caption          = Trumpington's famous V-sign in 2011\n|office          = [[Baroness-in-waiting]] <br>[[Government Whip]]\n|primeminister = [[John Major]]\n|term_start = 22 April 1992\n|term_end = 2 May 1997\n|predecessor = [[Jean Denton, Baroness Denton of Wakefield|The Baroness Denton]]\n|successor = [[Josie Farrington, Baroness Farrington of Ribbleton|The Baroness Farrington]]\n|primeminister1   = [[Margaret Thatcher]]\n|predecessor1 = [[Simon Arthur, 4th Baron Glenarthur|The Lord Glenarthur]]\n|successor1 = [[Caroline Cox, Baroness Cox|The Baroness Cox]]\n|term_start1      = 11 June 1983\n|term_end1        = 25 March 1985\n|office2           = [[Ministry of Agriculture, Fisheries and Food (United Kingdom)|Minister of State for Agriculture, Fisheries and Food]]<ref>Parliamentary Under-Secretary of State (1987-89)</ref>\n|primeminister2    = {{ubl|[[Margaret Thatcher]]|[[John Major]]}}\n|term_start2      = 13 June 1987\n|term_end2        = 14 April 1992\n|predecessor2 = [[John Gummer]]\n|successor2 = [[David Curry]]\n|office3          = [[Department of Health and Social Security|Parliamentary Under-Secretary of State for Health and Social Security]]\n|primeminister3 = [[Margaret Thatcher]]\n|predecessor3     = [[Simon Arthur, 4th Baron Glenarthur|The Lord Glenarthur]]\n|successor3 = [[Roger Bootle-Wilbraham, 7th Baron Skelmersdale|The Lord Skelmersdale]]\n|term_start3      = 30 March 1985\n|term_end3        = 13 June 1987\n|office4          = [[Mayor of Cambridge]]\n|term_start4      = 1970\n|term_end4        = 1971\n|predecessor4     = Brian Cooper\n|successor4       = Peter Wright\n|office5          = [[Members of the House of Lords|Member of the House of Lords]]<br>[[Lords Temporal|Lord Temporal]]\n|term_start5      = 4 February 1980\n|term_end5      = 24 October 2017<br>[[Life Peerage]]\n|birthname        = Jean Alys Campbell-Harris\n|birth_date       = {{Birth date|1922|10|23|df=y}}\n|birth_place      = London, England\n|death_date       = {{Death date and age|2018|11|26|1922|10|23|df=y}}\n|party            = [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]]<ref>{{cite web|df=dmy-all |url=http://www.parliament.uk/biographies/lords/baroness-trumpington/1820|title=Baronness Trumpington|publisher=Parliament of the United Kingdom|accessdate=8 June 2014}}</ref>\n|nationality      = British\n|spouse           = {{marriage|William Alan Barker|1954|1988|reason=died}}\n|children         = 1\n|occupation       = {{hlist|Politician|secretary}}\n}}\n'''Jean Alys Barker, Baroness Trumpington''', {{postnominals|country=GBR|sep=,|size=100%|DCVO|PC}} ({{nee|'''Campbell-Harris'''}}; 23 October 1922{{snd}}26 November 2018) was an English [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]] politician and member of the [[House of Lords]].<ref name=Telg9472666/> From an [[upper-class]] background, she was a [[socialite]] for years before entering politics.\n\n==Early life==\nTrumpington was born to Major Arthur Campbell-Harris and his American wife, Doris (n\u00e9e Robson), [[List of American heiresses|an heiress]] to a Chicago paint manufacturer. Trumpington's father was an officer in the [[7th Hariana Lancers]], part of the [[7th Lancers|Bengal Lancers]], who became ''[[aide-de-camp]]'' to the [[Viceroy of India]] and knew [[David Lloyd George]].\n\nTrumpington took dancing lessons at Madame Vacani's school in [[Knightsbridge]]. After two years she moved to the [[Ballet Rambert]] to learn under [[Pearl Argyle]]. Her mother had lost most of her inheritance in the [[Wall Street Crash of 1929]], including selling their home at 55, [[Great Cumberland Place]]. On the family's return from India, they lived in their house Rowling, [[Goodnestone, Dover|Goodnestone]], near [[Sandwich, Kent]], where Doris specialised in [[interior decorating]].<ref name=Telg9472666>{{cite news |df=dmy-all |url= https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/politics/9472666/Baroness-Trumpington-At-my-age-I-dont-give-a-damn-what-I-say.html |title= Baroness Trumpington: 'At my age, I don't give a damn what I say' |author= Grice, Elizabeth |newspaper=The Daily Telegraph |location=London |date=14 August 2012 |accessdate=3 December 2012}}</ref> When war broke out, the house, which was owned by the [[Board of Control for Lunacy and Mental Deficiency|Lunacy Commissioners]], was needed for Army [[billets]].  Spring Grove was a Queen Anne-style ten-bedroom mansion at [[Wye, Kent|Wye]], near Ashford in south Kent.<ref>Memoirs, pp.12, 14, 17, 21\u20132.</ref>\n\nEducated at [[Princess Helena College]], Trumpington, aged 15, left school never having taken an exam, although she was fluent in French, German and Italian. She then went to a [[finishing school]] in Paris to study art and literature.<ref name=Telg9472666/> Her father took her on holiday to [[Biarritz]]. {{quote|I was a very good, left-handed tennis player. I had coaching all year round and there was serious talk of junior Wimbledon.|author=Trumpington}} She spent a year at [[Montrichard]] receiving coaching from French tennis champion [[Jean Borotra]]. In Paris, she stayed with Madame de Benouville, whose husband Jean was a member of the royalist group [[Action Fran\u00e7aise]]. When war broke out, she returned to England\n\nShe had two brothers educated at [[Eton College|Eton]]; the elder, Alastair, was at [[Royal Naval College, Dartmouth]].\n\n==Bletchley Park, World War II and its aftermath==\nInitially during World War II, Lady Trumpington was attached to Lloyd George's Sussex arable farm, where she [[Women's Land Army (World War II)|worked on the land]] with his daughter, lodging with his then secretary/mistress and later wife [[Frances Stevenson]].<ref name=Telg9472666/> She recalled that Lloyd George used to find reasons to \"measure her\".<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|df=dmy-all |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-43756361|title=Obituary: Baroness Trumpington|date=2018-11-27|work=BBC News|access-date=2018-11-27|language=en-GB}}</ref> She then worked in [[Military intelligence|naval intelligence]] at [[Bletchley Park]] from October 1940, making use of her knowledge of the [[German language]] to crack naval codes.<ref name=Telg9472666/><ref name=secret>{{cite book|last=McKay|first=Sinclair|title=The Secret Life of Bletchley Park|year=2010|publisher=Aurum|isbn=978-1-84513-539-3|pages=60,125\u20136}}</ref><ref>{{YouTube|MDTarJmSboY|Bletchley Park Code Breakers&nbsp;\u2014 Baroness Trumpington}} {{retrieved||access-date=14 August 2016}}</ref>\n\nShe was billeted at [[Great Brickhill]] with [[W. J. Locke]]'s family, before moving to [[Passenham]] Manor, home of banker George Ansley. Her work was the centre of Z codes supervised by German-Jewish refugee, [[Walter Eytan|Walter Ettinghausen]]. Colleagues who became life-long friends included Sally, daughter of [[Baron Grantley|6th Lord Grantley]] (later [[Sarah Baring]]); Jean, daughter of [[James Graham, 6th Duke of Montrose]] (later [[Lady Jean Fforde]]<ref>{{cite news|title=Obituary: Lady Jean Fforde, aristocrat said to have auctioned off an earldom to pay for central heating|df=dmy-all |url=https://www.scotsman.com/news/obituaries/obituary-lady-jean-fforde-aristocrat-said-to-have-auctioned-off-an-earldom-to-pay-for-central-heating-1-4588888|accessdate=30 December 2017|work=www.scotsman.com|language=en}}</ref>); and [[Osla Benning]].\n\n{{quote|Life only really began when I went to Bletchley. That's when I made my real friends, and it was exciting being a part of something important. We used to meet up in [[Claridge's]], and throw bread at each other and sing and behave so badly. Five shillings was the most you could spend during the war, so it was as affordable as anywhere.<ref>{{cite news|df=dmy-all |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2014/apr/27/enigmatic-baroness-trumpington-bletchley-park-code-breaker|title=The enigmatic life of Lady Trumpington|newspaper=The Guardian|date=27 April 2014|accessdate=5 July 2016}}</ref>|author=Trumpington}}\n\nAt war's end, she spent four years working for the European Central Inland Transport Organization, shipping and distributing supplies to the war-torn continent with the same job description, filing clerk. But she was soon working as the effective transport manager from a 5th floor office in the [[Champs Elys\u00e9es]] above Mimi Pinson's nightclub. She went to parties at [[Paris Ritz|the Ritz]] and Crillion Club, frequented by politicians. Resident at 1 Place d'Alma, she worked briefly for the suave [[List of ambassadors of the United Kingdom to France|British ambassador]] [[Duff Cooper]], whose wife, previously [[Lady Diana Manners]], was a former actress she used to visit on Broadway. Lady Diana was courted by [[Ernest Bevin]],{{citation needed|date=December 2018}} the Labour cabinet minister. She maintained a passion for tennis and French fashion.<ref>Memoirs, p.71</ref>\n\nMoving in political circles, she returned to London to work for an imperial Conservative, [[Victor Montagu]], Viscount Hinchingbroke. He found her offices in 17 [[Great College Street]], but he was slightly drunk most of the time and inclined to nonchalance.<ref>see: Antony Colville Diaries</ref> On inheriting the title, he was forced to leave the House of Commons, but renounced his title to stand for election as an MP.\n\n==New York socialite==\nIn 1952, Trumpington moved to America, travelling on board [[RMS Mauretania (1938)|RMS ''Mauretania'']] and arriving at New York on 28 January.<ref>Memoirs, pp.98\u20139</ref> She shared a flat above the [[Stork Club]] on East [[52nd Street]], off [[Park Avenue]].<ref>Memoirs, p.100</ref> She was able to secure a position with an advertising agency, Fletcher Richards at the [[Rockefeller Center]], off 5th Avenue. Shopping on 6th Avenue, she made friends with Riv Winant, son of [[John Gilbert Winant]], a former American Ambassador to London; their friendship turned out to be long-term. They frequented haunts of wealthy high society New Yorkers such as the Round Hill Country Club, Greenwich, Connecticut, and the [[River House (New York City)|River Club]] of New York City, and the homes of East Hampton, Long Island, with membership of the exclusive [[Maidstone Club]].  Fascinated by wealth,(please cite source saying she was \u201cfascinated by wealth\u201d)  she got on the guest list of billionaire philanthropist, [[Walter Annenberg]], a Jewish \u00e9migr\u00e9. Ronnie Furse taught her to water-ski in the Chesapeake Bay.<ref>Memoirs, p.107, 116.</ref> For her, the physical prowess was unnecessary, but part of the tour. Working as a secretary, she moved into a flat on 137 East 73rd Street next to Furse.<ref>Memoirs, pp.110\u201311</ref>\n\nWhilst in America, she met an Englishman, (William) Alan Barker, [[Master of Arts (Oxbridge and Dublin)|M.A. (Cantab.)]], a Master at [[Eton College]] and formerly a Captain in the [[Royal Artillery]],<ref>Coming up Trumps: A Memoir, Jean Trumpington, Pan Macmillan, 2014</ref> wounded in the leg in Normandy on 16 June 1944. While working on the Harkness Commonwealth Fellowship in New York, he offered to bring her back to London.<ref>Memoirs, p.118.</ref>  She returned to Britain during the [[London Season]] and [[Coronation of Queen Elizabeth II|Queen Elizabeth II's coronation]], and they were engaged in October 1953.<ref>''New York Herald'', 22 October 1953; ''New York Times'', 22 October 1953; ''The Times'', 2 November 1953</ref> Lady Trumpington left New York for the last time by liner on 15 December. She was forced to apply for a licence to the [[Solicitor General for England and Wales|Solicitor-General]] to become the first couple in modern times to hold a wedding at the Chapel of the [[Royal Hospital Chelsea]], which took place on 18 March 1954.<ref name=Telg9472666/>\n\n==Return to England==\nAfter working at Eton, her husband was Headmaster of [[The Leys School]] in Cambridge between 1958 and 1975, before moving to [[University College School, London]]. She played host to the rich and famous, often travelling abroad to raise funds for The Leys from parents and old boys. They invited the local dignitaries [[Edward Heath]] MP and the [[Katharine, Duchess of Kent|Duchess of Kent]] with the [[Prime Minister of Singapore]] to an open day. In 1961, the [[Queen Mother]] came to tea, and then again to open an extension to buildings in 1973.\n\nOn the day that [[Harold Wilson]] resigned in 1970, she invited Heath to view the cricket pitches, which was reciprocated by a visit to [[10 Downing Street|No.10]]. Other royalty continued to attend from Bahrain and Tonga. She promoted the school with her own brand of conservatism, taking care of mental health and epilepsy in the school. With Eton's help they started a boat club, spent time at [[Cliveden]] and in 1962 included among their friends, the Astors.<ref>Trumpington, p.162</ref> The Macmillan era was rounded off with a world tour to drum up school business.\n\nThe couple had one son, Adam Campbell Barker born on 31 August 1955. Adam was educated at [[King's School, Canterbury]] and [[Queens' College, Cambridge]]. He qualified as a [[solicitor]] and, later, as a [[barrister]]. He was married in 1985 to Elizabeth Mary, daughter of Eric Marsden OBE of Stourpaine Manor, Blandford.<ref name=Telg9472666/>\n\n==Conservative politics==\nSince 1945, Mother and Baby Homes (otherwise known as [[maternity home]]s) had been places for the poor to wean their offspring. She was appointed governor of the one in [[Cambridge]], and moved to Cambridge where her voluntary work continued.<ref>Trumpington, pp.177\u20138</ref> The United Cambridge Hospital Board, the Cambridge Social Services Committee, and the [[Museum of Cambridge|Cambridge Folk Museum]] all received her patronage. She was a member of the Rheumatism and Arthritis Association, which began serious research work on debilitation at Cambridge laboratories. She gained public notoriety for personally tackling{{dub|date=November 2018}} the 'Cambridge Rapist' in her own home, for whom the police had been searching for years without success; a burglar turned out to be the wanted felon masquerading as a door-to-door salesman calling himself MacFisheries.{{citation needed|date=November 2018}}\n\nIn 1963, she was elected as councillor for [[Trumpington, Cambridgeshire|Trumpington]] on [[Cambridge City Council]]. In 1971/2, she served as [[Mayor of Cambridge]] which she described as a \"[[wikt:folderol|folderol]]\". That office was followed by appointment to the Cambridge bench as a [[Justice of the Peace]] from 1972. She granted the Freedom of Cambridge to [[RAF Oakington]], revived the town's market, installed a travel centre, and built an entrance hall to the railway station. She opened the [[Elizabeth Way Bridge]] with former Conservative cabinet minister [[Rab Butler]], [[High Steward (academia)|High Steward of Cambridge University]]. She arranged to \"twin\" Cambridge with three other great university cities, [[Florence]], [[Heidelberg]] and [[Split, Croatia|Split]]. She raised funds for [[Addenbrooke's Hospital]] and the Indo-Pakistan War Relief Fund, and undertook a swimathon.\n\nBefore the local government and administration of justice re-organisation, it was usual for the upper classes to sit on the bench as a matter of [[nobless oblige|public duty]]. She re-entered politics in 1973, when she was elected to [[Cambridgeshire County Council]] for the Trumpington division but resigned in 1975 over the rapist scandal.<ref name=Debretts/>{{clarify|date=November 2018}} She sought election to [[Parliament of the United Kingdom|Parliament]], and reached the short list for the [[Isle of Ely (UK Parliament constituency)|Isle of Ely]] for the [[October 1974 United Kingdom general election|October 1974 election]].<ref name=Telg9472666/> (Dr [[Thomas Stuttaford]] was selected instead and lost to [[Clement Freud]].) That year marked a watershed in her political career. Stepping up a gear, she moved into a visibly national profile: her son was by now fully grown and starting a career. Continuing a gradual move up the career ladder into public life, Barker matured into a serious-minded public figure; she was appointed to the Board of Visitors of the women's gaol attached to [[HM Prison Pentonville|Pentonville Prison]] in London. She was one of the few who could get along well with the leader of her party, [[Margaret Thatcher]].<ref>Walker, Andy. [https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-27888144 \"Baroness Trumpington profile: From Lloyd George to the Lords\"]. ''[[BBC News]]'', 11 November 2014</ref>\n\nIn addition, the former councillor was appointed by the Labour government to the [[Mental Health Tribunal]], before [[care in the community|community care]] had been introduced. The following year, 1976, she was made a General Commissioner for Taxes, based on a competent showing with the city's finances. She served on various public bodies, including chair of the Air Transport Users Committee (1979\u201380).<ref name=Telg9472666/> One of the first questions she asked in the Lords was about improving the airmail service, in which area she was regarded an expert.<ref>Lord Trenchard said \"like Lady Trumpington's expert knowledge in relation to air mail\". HL Deb 30 April 1980 vol 408 cc1284-333 Retrieved 22 July 2016.</ref> The binding [[Official Secrets Act#United Kingdom|Official Secrets]] clause was repealed, privatisation followed, and profitability indexation restored to Air Mail services.<ref>{{cite web|df=dmy-all |url=http://hansard.millbanksystems.com/lords/1980/apr/30/post-office-services-1#S5LV0408P0_19800430_HOL_160|title=POST OFFICE SERVICES (Hansard, 30 April 1980)|website=hansard.millbanksystems.com}}</ref>\n\nHer interest in women's affairs became known for all the world to see when Thatcher became Prime Minister. Appointed as UK Representative to the [[UN Commission on the Status of Women]] it was her role to promote women's equality, marriage and divorce, healthcare, child-rearing, and human rights. She had an extensive address book in the United States; managing British interests on the Council in New York gave her a social profile that befitted her class status and ambition, but was nonetheless useful networking for the British Government.<ref>Burke's Peerage, 107th edition, vol.III.</ref> Belated recognition came from a Labour peeress:\n\n{{quote|On a different canvas, the noble Baroness, Lady Trumpington, then UK representative at the UN Commission on the Status of Women, helped to unite the international voice of women through her irresistible humour and sense of fun. It was good to be so involved in those days.<ref>{{cite web|df=dmy-all |url=http://hansard.millbanksystems.com/lords/2004/nov/23/address-in-reply-to-her-majestys-most#S5LV0667P0_20041123_HOL_68|title=Address in Reply to Her Majesty's Most Gracious Speech (Hansard, 23 November 2004)|website=hansard.millbanksystems.com}}</ref>}} Sent by Mrs Thatcher to Copenhagen, she headed a delegation to UK's first female ambassador, [[Anne Warburton]]. At the UN she crossed the floor to greet [[Suzanne Mubarak]], who made a brave speech for advancing peace in the Middle East.\n\nLady Trumpington was a steward of [[Folkestone Racecourse]] (1980\u201392).<ref name=Telg9472666/> In 1980, she was made an Honorary Fellow of [[Lucy Cavendish College]], Cambridge. She was a member of the Farmers\u2019 Club and Grillion's Club in London.<ref>Burke's 107th ed. (London 2003), vol.III, p.1949</ref>\n\n==Ministerial office from the Lords==\n{{more citations needed|section|date=January 2019}}\nIn almost her first debate she found herself on two sides of the same debate: discussing Clause no.23 amendment sponsored by Duke of Norfolk to Education Bill No. 2 1980.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://hansard.millbanksystems.com/lords/1980/mar/13/education-no-2-bill#S5LV0406P0_19800313_HOL_125|title=EDUCATION (No. 2) BILL (Hansard, 13 March 1980)|website=hansard.millbanksystems.com}}</ref> In June 1983, she joined the Lords [[Works of Art Committee]]. She became a resident expert on the committee, where she sat until 2010.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.parliament.uk/biographies/lords/baroness-trumpington/1820|title=Baroness Trumpington|website=UK Parliament}}</ref>\n\nOn leaving the UN post and entering the House of Lords, she was introduced as a [[Baroness-in-waiting]] from 1983 to 1985. Thatcher recognised her capabilities when she was given a ministerial post. Despite being in the Lords as [[Parliamentary Under-Secretary of State]] at the [[Department of Health and Social Security]] from 1985\u201387, during which time she smoked cigarettes, and in spite of a deep concern for women's mental health with numerous charities, she would ''in perpetuum'' champion the cause of smokers to do what they wanted.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://hansard.millbanksystems.com/lords/2004/dec/21/administration-and-works-committee#S5LV0667P0_20041221_HOL_153|title=Administration and Works Committee (Hansard, 21 December 2004)|website=hansard.millbanksystems.com}}</ref> A stubborn streak of wilful independence was typical of the Thatcherite in her, which she never lost up until her final ''verbatim'' speech in the Lords.<ref>Weds 15 March 2005,\n[http://hansard.millbanksystems.com/lords/2005/mar/09/smoking-in-public-places#S5LV0670P0_20050309_HOL_17 Hansard01]\nsee also: [http://parlipapers.chadwyck.co.uk/hansard/fullrec.do?area=hcpp&resultNum=1&entries=116&source=config6.cfg&queryId=../session/1469189082_22372&fulltexthits=106 Hansard HL Deb 09 March 2005 vol 670 cc727-9]</ref>\n\nMoving to the Ministry of Agriculture, which suited her temperament better than social security, at the height of the Thatcher boom period from 1987 to 1989, she was made [[Parliamentary Under-Secretary]]. She was promoted to number two at the ministry in 1989 when the Prime Minister was still creating [[hereditary peerage]]s; she valued her friendship and support. She continued until 1992, serving during John Major's administration as [[Minister of State]] at the [[Ministry of Agriculture, Fisheries and Food (United Kingdom)|Ministry of Agriculture, Fisheries and Food]], when at age 69 she was the oldest female minister ever.<ref name=Telg9472666/><ref name=Debretts/>\n\nHer last role was once again as a Baroness-in-waiting to the Queen<ref name=\":0\"/> from 1992\u201397, when a change of government ended her career. Acting in the capacity as a whip and a courtier, she felt compelled to attend at the bedside of [[Sally Mugabe]] in a London Hospital. She also received [[Mohammed Zahir Shah]], the last king of Afghanistan, on behalf of the Queen. On several occasions during the 1990s, Lady Trumpington became acquainted with the [[New Labour]] opposition leaders, [[Tony Blair]] and [[Gordon Brown]] at Court. She was one of the few officials on hand in 1990 to recognise [[Mongolian Revolution of 1990|the new State of Mongolia]], subsequently travelling to Ulan Bator to deal with KGB-backed Russian investors on a construction project.{{citation needed|date=January 2019}}\n\nThe [[Blair ministry|New Labour government]] therefore decided to appoint her an Extraordinary Baroness-in-Waiting from 1998, given her many years of experience at Court. During the Labour government, she was consistently on the side of traditionalists. She voted often in favour of [[university tuition fees]] and raising the cap to \u00a39,000; opposed constitutional reform, telling the Lords that she believed in the [[first past the post|first-past-the-post system]]; and against the ban on [[fox hunting]]. Lady Trumpington was broadly in favour of [[Brexit]], particularly the diminution of EU integration. She voted against the bill to make a referendum necessary to transfer powers back from EU to UK.<ref>{{cite web|df=dmy-all |url=https://www.theyworkforyou.com/peer/13538/baroness_trumpington|title=Baroness Trumpington - TheyWorkForYou|website=TheyWorkForYou}}</ref> Trumpington remained a principled opponent of soft measures on crime. Consistently supportive of tough measures, she was appointed Trustee of [[Crimestoppers]] in 2004. This tied in closely with ongoing visitations to [[Pentonville Prison]], as Crimestoppers' emphasis was specific to schoolchildren and youth offending. She opposed \"walking free\" and [[community sentencing]]; her disarming charm when discoursing about conditions in Britain's jails alerted the Lords perspective on the significance of public participation in [[crime reduction]] initiatives.<ref>{{cite web|df=dmy-all |url=http://hansard.millbanksystems.com/lords/2004/dec/08/crime-prevention#S5LV0667P0_20041208_HOL_343.|title=Crime Prevention (Hansard, 8 December 2004)|website=hansard.millbanksystems.com}}</ref>\n\nHer sense of order, propriety and taste got her into trouble: mocked by a Labour peeress for commenting on the drab and dishevelled appearance of the House of Lords, she more than once appeared a martinet for insisting on \"[[dress code]]\".<ref>Baroness Billingham HL Deb 23 November 2004 vol 667 cc5-20 Retrieved 22 July 2016.</ref> On another occasion she gave a [[V sign as an insult|V-sign]] to [[Tom King, Baron King of Bridgwater|Lord King of Bridgwater]] in the House of Lords, 10 November 2011 when he referred to her advanced age during a [[Remembrance Day]] debate.<ref name=Telg9472666/><ref name=\"theguardian.com\">[https://www.theguardian.com/media/mediamonkeyblog/2011/nov/14/lords-v-sign-king \"House of Lords' V-sign makes X-rated viewing\"], The Guardian (London), 14 November 2011.</ref>\n\nWhen she tried to debate the \"plight of rural veterinary practices\", the peeress pretended to be deaf: she had long railed against the most absurd forms of political correctness.{{Clarify|date=January 2019}} In 2000\u201301, she was made President of the [[South of England Show|South of England Agricultural Show]], taking the opportunity to promote animal health, a cause for which she had in 1995 been awarded an Honorary Membership of the [[British Veterinary Association]], in response to her work in that ministry.<ref>Trumpington, p. 210</ref> Declining rural practices was caused directly by the government's farming policies; the yawning gap between policy and practice exposed weaknesses in the EFRACOM report. She had initiated the debate on 24 June 2004, and was widely praised for so doing.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://hansard.millbanksystems.com/lords/2004/jun/24/veterinary-practices#S5LV0662P0_20040624_HOL_185|title=Veterinary Practices (Hansard, 24 June 2004)|website=hansard.millbanksystems.com}}</ref> Throughout her career, she was notable for having raised uncomfortable truths about topics most politicians have avoided, such as the plight of women in prisons, or the fate of single mothers with mental health issues.{{citation needed|date=January 2019}}\n\nIn December 2012, she acknowledged the campaign for the government to give official recognition to the work of [[Alan Turing]]. In a letter to the ''[[Daily Telegraph]]'', the signatories, including [[Stephen Hawking]], the physicist; [[Martin Rees, Baron Rees of Ludlow|Lord Rees]], the [[astronomer royal]]; and [[Paul Nurse|Sir Paul Nurse]], [[List of presidents of the Royal Society|the president of the Royal Society]], called on Prime Minister [[David Cameron]] to support [[Alan Turing#Government apology and pardon support|a pardon for Turing's 1952 conviction for homosexuality]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2013/jul/20/alan-turing-posthumous-pardon|title=Pardoning Alan Turing is a pointless exercise|author=Ben Summerskill|work=The Guardian|accessdate=3 January 2016}}</ref> Trumpington worked at Bletchley Park during the war at the same time as Turing, commenting only on his presence.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-2434273/Baroness-Trumpington-THAT-finger-gesture-scared-PM-dared-touch-up.html|title=Baroness Trumpington, THAT two-finger gesture and how she scared off PM who dared touch her up|date=27 September 2013|work=Mail Online|accessdate=3 January 2016}}</ref>\n\nShe retired from the House of Lords on 24 October 2017, one day after her 95th birthday.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.parliament.uk/biographies/lords/baroness-trumpington/1820|title=Baroness Trumpington|publisher=[[Parliament of the United Kingdom|UK Parliament]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Baroness Trumpington Retires|df=dmy-all |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/amp/uk-politics-41550627}}</ref>\n\n==Honours==\nTrumpington was appointed an [[National Order of Merit (France)|Officer of the National Order of Merit]] by the French Republic.<ref name=Debretts>{{cite web|url=http://www.debretts.com/people/biographies/browse/t/4080/Jean+Alys.aspx|title=The Rt Hon the Baroness Trumpington, DCVO, PC|publisher=[[Debrett's]]|accessdate=3 December 2012}}</ref> On 4 February 1980 she was created a [[life peer]], choosing the title Baroness Trumpington, of [[Sandwich, Kent|Sandwich]] in the [[County of Kent]].<ref name=Telg9472666/><ref>{{London Gazette|issue=48091|date=7 February 1980|page=1977}}</ref> She was appointed a [[Royal Victorian Order|Dame Commander of the Royal Victorian Order]] in 2005.<ref name=Telg9472666/><ref>{{London Gazette|issue=57665|date=11 June 2005|page=3|supp=y}}</ref> Leaving government she was granted an Honorary Fellowship of the [[Royal College of Pathologists]] (FRCPath). Two years later she was recognised for her voluntary activities as Honorary Associate of the Royal College of Volunteer Services (ARCVS).{{citation needed|date=December 2017}}\n\n==Media==\nAs a castaway on ''[[Desert Island Discs]]'' in 1990 she chose as her luxury item the [[Crown Jewels of the United Kingdom|Crown Jewels]] in order to maximise her chances of being rescued.<ref name=desertisland>{{cite web|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/radio4/features/desert-island-discs/castaway/2e3554a8|title=Desert island Discs}}</ref>\n\nIn 2011, she published a jaunty [[ghost-written]] memoir, ''Coming Up Trumps''. In the preface, she wrote she was persuaded by huge demands from her friends and colleagues to have an autobiography published.<ref>Jean Trumpington, Coming Up Trumps: A Memoir, London: Macmillan, 2011.<!-- ISSN/ISBN needed --></ref>\n\nOn 30 November 2012, Trumpington was a guest panellist on the BBC TV's satirical news quiz ''[[Have I Got News for You]]''; at the age of 90 she was the oldest guest to have appeared on the programme. In December 2013 she was a guest on [[BBC Three]] chat show ''[[Backchat (2013 TV series)|Backchat]]'' with [[Jack Whitehall|Jack]] and [[Michael Whitehall]]. In 2014 she was a guest judge in the finals of the ''[[Great British Menu]]''.\n\nAt the end of December 2017, she was [[List of Today programme guest editors|one of the guest editors]] for BBC Radio 4's prestigious [[Today programme|''Today'' programme]]. Topics she chose to highlight included her long-standing [[Prostitution in the United Kingdom#Current legal status|campaign to legalise brothels]]; [[Sangita Myska]] was tasked with interviewing a brothel keeper, a sex worker, and a woman who had escaped the sex industry. Another topic was living with incurable diseases such as [[Crohn's disease|Crohn's]]. [[John Humphrys]] interviewed her about her life and career, when she credited good luck for much of her success.\n<ref>{{cite web|publisher=BBC Radio 4|title=Today|date=29 December 2017|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b09jqtjx|accessdate=29 December 2017}}</ref>\n\nShe was referenced as suffering from the fictional 'Slimmels disease' in the spoof news and current affairs satire [[The Day Today]].\n\n==Later life and death==\nLady Trumpington was widowed in 1988.<ref name=Telg9472666/> In later interviews with ''The Guardian'' she described enjoying her grandchildren. She also enjoyed [[contract bridge]], [[needlepoint]] and [[horse racing]].<ref name=Debretts/>  In January 2010, while she was out, her flat in [[Battersea]] caught fire; her possessions were badly damaged.<ref name=Telg9472666/>\n\nShe died in her sleep on 26 November 2018. Her death was confirmed by her son, Adam Barker on [[Twitter]] later that night. He wrote: \"My mother passed away this afternoon in her sleep&nbsp;... she had a bloody good innings.\"<ref>https://www.shropshirestar.com/news/uk-news/2018/11/26/baroness-trumpington-bletchley-park-code-breaker-with-celebrated-v-sign-dies/</ref>\n\n==Arms==\n{{Infobox COA wide\n|image = [[File:Coronet of a British Baron.svg|centre|100px]] [[File:Arms of Jean Barker, Baroness Trumpington.svg|centre|200px]]\n|coronet = A [[Coronet|Coronet of a Baron]]\n|escutcheon = ''Gyronny of eight Ermine and Azure three Hedgehogs two and one Or.''<ref>{{cite web|df=dmy-all |url=http://www.cracroftspeerage.co.uk/online/content/lp1958%20t.htm?zoom_highlight=trumpington |title=Life Peerages - T |publisher=Cracroftspeerage.co.uk |date= |accessdate=2018-12-30}}</ref>\n|supporters =  Dexter: a Boxer Bitch; Sinister: a Bay Colt, both proper\n|motto = ''Gagne Tout Sans Atouts'' (\"Win all with no trumps\")\n|orders = [[Royal Victorian Order]]\n}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n'''Bibliography'''\n* {{cite book|first=Jean|last= Trumpington|title=Coming Up Trumps: A Memoir|location=London|publisher=Macmillan|date=2011|isbn=978-1-4472-5677-9}}\n\n==External links==\n{{wikisource|Barker, Jean, Baroness Trumpington}}\n{{wikiquote|Barker, Jean, Baroness Trumpington}}\n* {{cite news|df=dmy-all |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2014/apr/27/enigmatic-baroness-trumpington-bletchley-park-code-breaker|title= Enigmatic Baroness Trumpington|author= Cooke, Rachel|newspaper= [[The Guardian]]|date=27 April 2014 |accessdate= 12 January 2019}}\n* {{cite news|df=dmy-all |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-27888144|title= Baroness Trumpington profile: From Lloyd George to the Lords|date=11 November 2014 |work=[[BBC News]]|author=Walker, Andy|accessdate=12 January 2019}}\n* {{cite news|df=dmy-all |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/politics/9472666/Baroness-Trumpington-At-my-age-I-dont-give-a-damn-what-I-say.html|title= Baroness Trumpington: 'At my age I don\u2019t give a damn what I say'|date= 14 August 2012|work=[[The Daily Telegraph]] |author= Grice, Elizabeth|accessdate=12 January 2019}}\n* {{cite web|df=dmy-all |url=http://www.parliament.uk/biographies/lords/baroness-trumpington/1820|title= Baroness Trumpington|website=Parliament.uk |accessdate=7 July 2016}}\n* {{cite journal|df=dmy-all |url=http://jmg.bmj.com/content/24/4/235.full.pdf|title=Visit of Health Minister to Clinical Genetics Society |journal=[[Journal of Medical Genetics]] |year=1987 |volume=24 |pp=235\u2013249 |accessdate=22 July 2016}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Trumpington, Jean Barker, Baroness}}\n[[Category:1922 births]]\n[[Category:2018 deaths]]\n[[Category:Bletchley Park people]]\n[[Category:Bletchley Park women]]\n[[Category:Conservative Party (UK) Baronesses- and Lords-in-Waiting]]\n[[Category:Conservative Party (UK) life peers]]\n[[Category:Members of Cambridgeshire County Council]]\n[[Category:Dames Commander of the Royal Victorian Order]]\n[[Category:English autobiographers]]\n[[Category:English expatriates in the United States]]\n[[Category:English people of American descent]]\n[[Category:Female life peers]]\n[[Category:Mayors of Cambridge]]\n[[Category:Members of the Privy Council of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Officers of the National Order of Merit (France)]]\n[[Category:People from Trumpington]]\n[[Category:Socialites from London]]\n[[Category:Women autobiographers]]\n[[Category:Women mayors of places in England]]\n", "text_old": "{{redirect|Jean Barker|the film editor|Jean Barker (film editor)}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2013}}\n{{EngvarB|date=September 2019}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|honorific-prefix = [[The Right Honourable]]\n|name             = The Baroness Trumpington\n|honorific-suffix = [[Royal Victorian Order|DCVO]] [[Her Majesty's Most Honourable Privy Council|PC]]\n|image            = Baroness Trumpington 2011.jpg\n|caption          = Trumpington's famous V-sign in 2011\n|office          = [[Baroness-in-waiting]] <br>[[Government Whip]]\n|primeminister = [[John Major]]\n|term_start = 22 April 1992\n|term_end = 2 May 1997\n|predecessor = [[Jean Denton, Baroness Denton of Wakefield|The Baroness Denton]]\n|successor = [[Josie Farrington, Baroness Farrington of Ribbleton|The Baroness Farrington]]\n|primeminister1   = [[Margaret Thatcher]]\n|predecessor1 = [[Simon Arthur, 4th Baron Glenarthur|The Lord Glenarthur]]\n|successor1 = [[Caroline Cox, Baroness Cox|The Baroness Cox]]\n|term_start1      = 11 June 1983\n|term_end1        = 25 March 1985\n|office2           = [[Ministry of Agriculture, Fisheries and Food (United Kingdom)|Minister of State for Agriculture, Fisheries and Food]]<ref>Parliamentary Under-Secretary of State (1987-89)</ref>\n|primeminister2    = {{ubl|[[Margaret Thatcher]]|[[John Major]]}}\n|term_start2      = 13 June 1987\n|term_end2        = 14 April 1992\n|predecessor2 = [[John Gummer]]\n|successor2 = [[David Curry]]\n|office3          = [[Department of Health and Social Security|Parliamentary Under-Secretary of State for Health and Social Security]]\n|primeminister3 = [[Margaret Thatcher]]\n|predecessor3     = [[Simon Arthur, 4th Baron Glenarthur|The Lord Glenarthur]]\n|successor3 = [[Roger Bootle-Wilbraham, 7th Baron Skelmersdale|The Lord Skelmersdale]]\n|term_start3      = 30 March 1985\n|term_end3        = 13 June 1987\n|office4          = [[Mayor of Cambridge]]\n|term_start4      = 1970\n|term_end4        = 1971\n|predecessor4     = Brian Cooper\n|successor4       = Peter Wright\n|office5          = [[Members of the House of Lords|Member of the House of Lords]]<br>[[Lords Temporal|Lord Temporal]]\n|term_start5      = 4 February 1980\n|term_end5      = 24 October 2017<br>[[Life Peerage]]\n|birthname        = Jean Alys Campbell-Harris\n|birth_date       = {{Birth date|1922|10|23|df=y}}\n|birth_place      = London, England\n|death_date       = {{Death date and age|2018|11|26|1922|10|23|df=y}}\n|party            = [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]]<ref>{{cite web|df=dmy-all |url=http://www.parliament.uk/biographies/lords/baroness-trumpington/1820|title=Baronness Trumpington|publisher=Parliament of the United Kingdom|accessdate=8 June 2014}}</ref>\n|nationality      = British\n|spouse           = {{marriage|William Alan Barker|1954|1988|reason=died}}\n|children         = 1\n|occupation       = {{hlist|Politician|secretary}}\n}}\n'''Jean Alys Barker, Baroness Trumpington''', {{postnominals|country=GBR|sep=,|size=100%|DCVO|PC}} ({{nee|'''Campbell-Harris'''}}; 23 October 1922{{snd}}26 November 2018) was an English [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]] politician and member of the [[House of Lords]].<ref name=Telg9472666/> From an [[upper-class]] background, she was a [[socialite]] for years before entering politics.\n\n==Early life==\nTrumpington was born to Major Arthur Campbell-Harris and his American wife, Doris (n\u00e9e Robson), [[List of American heiresses|an heiress]] to a Chicago paint manufacturer. Trumpington's father was an officer in the [[7th Hariana Lancers]], part of the [[7th Lancers|Bengal Lancers]], who became ''[[aide-de-camp]]'' to the [[Viceroy of India]] and knew [[David Lloyd George]].\n\nTrumpington took dancing lessons at Madame Vacani's school in [[Knightsbridge]]. After two years she moved to the [[Ballet Rambert]] to learn under [[Pearl Argyle]]. Her mother had lost most of her inheritance in the [[Wall Street Crash of 1929]], including selling their home at 55, [[Great Cumberland Place]]. On the family's return from India, they lived in their house Rowling, [[Goodnestone, Dover|Goodnestone]], near [[Sandwich, Kent]], where Doris specialised in [[interior decorating]].<ref name=Telg9472666>{{cite news |df=dmy-all |url= https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/politics/9472666/Baroness-Trumpington-At-my-age-I-dont-give-a-damn-what-I-say.html |title= Baroness Trumpington: 'At my age, I don't give a damn what I say' |author= Grice, Elizabeth |newspaper=The Daily Telegraph |location=London |date=14 August 2012 |accessdate=3 December 2012}}</ref> When war broke out, the house, which was owned by the [[Board of Control for Lunacy and Mental Deficiency|Lunacy Commissioners]], was needed for Army [[billets]].  Spring Grove was a Queen Anne-style ten-bedroom mansion at [[Wye, Kent|Wye]], near Ashford in south Kent.<ref>Memoirs, pp.12, 14, 17, 21\u20132.</ref>\n\nEducated at [[Princess Helena College]], Trumpington, aged 15, left school never having taken an exam, although she was fluent in French, German and Italian. She then went to a [[finishing school]] in Paris to study art and literature.<ref name=Telg9472666/> Her father took her on holiday to [[Biarritz]]. {{quote|I was a very good, left-handed tennis player. I had coaching all year round and there was serious talk of junior Wimbledon.|author=Trumpington}} She spent a year at [[Montrichard]] receiving coaching from French tennis champion [[Jean Borotra]]. In Paris, she stayed with Madame de Benouville, whose husband Jean was a member of the royalist group [[Action Fran\u00e7aise]]. When war broke out, she returned to England\n\nShe had two brothers educated at [[Eton College|Eton]]; the elder, Alastair, was at [[Royal Naval College, Dartmouth]].\n\n==Bletchley Park, World War II and its aftermath==\nInitially during World War II, Lady Trumpington was attached to Lloyd George's Sussex arable farm, where she [[Women's Land Army (World War II)|worked on the land]] with his daughter, lodging with his then secretary/mistress and later wife [[Frances Stevenson]].<ref name=Telg9472666/> She recalled that Lloyd George used to find reasons to \"measure her\".<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|df=dmy-all |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-43756361|title=Obituary: Baroness Trumpington|date=2018-11-27|work=BBC News|access-date=2018-11-27|language=en-GB}}</ref> She then worked in [[Military intelligence|naval intelligence]] at [[Bletchley Park]] from October 1940, making use of her knowledge of the [[German language]] to crack naval codes.<ref name=Telg9472666/><ref name=secret>{{cite book|last=McKay|first=Sinclair|title=The Secret Life of Bletchley Park|year=2010|publisher=Aurum|isbn=978-1-84513-539-3|pages=60,125\u20136}}</ref><ref>{{YouTube|MDTarJmSboY|Bletchley Park Code Breakers&nbsp;\u2014 Baroness Trumpington}} {{retrieved||access-date=14 August 2016}}</ref>\n\nShe was billeted at [[Great Brickhill]] with [[W. J. Locke]]'s family, before moving to [[Passenham]] Manor, home of banker George Ansley. Her work was the centre of Z codes supervised by German-Jewish refugee, [[Walter Eytan|Walter Ettinghausen]]. Colleagues who became life-long friends included Sally, daughter of [[Baron Grantley|6th Lord Grantley]] (later [[Sarah Baring]]); Jean, daughter of [[James Graham, 6th Duke of Montrose]] (later [[Lady Jean Fforde]]<ref>{{cite news|title=Obituary: Lady Jean Fforde, aristocrat said to have auctioned off an earldom to pay for central heating|df=dmy-all |url=https://www.scotsman.com/news/obituaries/obituary-lady-jean-fforde-aristocrat-said-to-have-auctioned-off-an-earldom-to-pay-for-central-heating-1-4588888|accessdate=30 December 2017|work=www.scotsman.com|language=en}}</ref>); and [[Osla Benning]].\n\n{{quote|Life only really began when I went to Bletchley. That's when I made my real friends, and it was exciting being a part of something important. We used to meet up in [[Claridge's]], and throw bread at each other and sing and behave so badly. Five shillings was the most you could spend during the war, so it was as affordable as anywhere.<ref>{{cite news|df=dmy-all |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2014/apr/27/enigmatic-baroness-trumpington-bletchley-park-code-breaker|title=The enigmatic life of Lady Trumpington|newspaper=The Guardian|date=27 April 2014|accessdate=5 July 2016}}</ref>|author=Trumpington}}\n\nAt war's end, she spent four years working for the European Central Inland Transport Organization, shipping and distributing supplies to the war-torn continent with the same job description, filing clerk. But she was soon working as the effective transport manager from a 5th floor office in the [[Champs Elys\u00e9es]] above Mimi Pinson's nightclub. She went to parties at [[Paris Ritz|the Ritz]] and Crillion Club, frequented by politicians. Resident at 1 Place d'Alma, she worked briefly for the suave [[List of ambassadors of the United Kingdom to France|British ambassador]] [[Duff Cooper]], whose wife, previously [[Lady Diana Manners]], was a former actress she used to visit on Broadway. Lady Diana was courted by [[Ernest Bevin]],{{citation needed|date=December 2018}} the Labour cabinet minister. She maintained a passion for tennis and French fashion.<ref>Memoirs, p.71</ref>\n\nMoving in political circles, she returned to London to work for an imperial Conservative, [[Victor Montagu]], Viscount Hinchingbroke. He found her offices in 17 [[Great College Street]], but he was slightly drunk most of the time and inclined to nonchalance.<ref>see: Antony Colville Diaries</ref> On inheriting the title, he was forced to leave the House of Commons, but renounced his title to stand for election as an MP.\n\n==New York socialite==\nIn 1952, Trumpington moved to America, travelling on board [[RMS Mauretania (1938)|RMS ''Mauretania'']] and arriving at New York on 28 January.<ref>Memoirs, pp.98\u20139</ref> She shared a flat above the [[Stork Club]] on East [[52nd Street]], off [[Park Avenue]].<ref>Memoirs, p.100</ref> She was able to secure a position with an advertising agency, Fletcher Richards at the [[Rockefeller Center]], off 5th Avenue. Shopping on 6th Avenue, she made friends with Riv Winant, son of [[John Gilbert Winant]], a former American Ambassador to London; their friendship turned out to be long-term. They frequented haunts of wealthy high society New Yorkers such as the Round Hill Country Club, Greenwich, Connecticut, and the [[River House (New York City)|River Club]] of New York City, and the homes of East Hampton, Long Island, with membership of the exclusive [[Maidstone Club]].  Fascinated by wealth,(please cite source saying she was \u201cfascinated by wealth\u201d)  she got on the guest list of billionaire philanthropist, [[Walter Annenberg]], a Jewish \u00e9migr\u00e9. Ronnie Furse taught her to water-ski in the Chesapeake Bay.<ref>Memoirs, p.107, 116.</ref> For her, the physical prowess was unnecessary, but part of the tour. Working as a secretary, she moved into a flat on 137 East 73rd Street next to Furse.<ref>Memoirs, pp.110\u201311</ref>\n\nWhilst in America, she met an Englishman, (William) Alan Barker, [[Master of Arts (Oxbridge and Dublin)|M.A. (Cantab.)]], a Master at [[Eton College]] and formerly a Captain in the [[Royal Artillery]],<ref>Coming up Trumps: A Memoir, Jean Trumpington, Pan Macmillan, 2014</ref> wounded in the leg in Normandy on 16 June 1944. While working on the Harkness Commonwealth Fellowship in New York, he offered to bring her back to London.<ref>Memoirs, p.118.</ref>  She returned to Britain during the [[London Season]] and [[Coronation of Queen Elizabeth II|Queen Elizabeth II's coronation]], and they were engaged in October 1953.<ref>''New York Herald'', 22 October 1953; ''New York Times'', 22 October 1953; ''The Times'', 2 November 1953</ref> Lady Trumpington left New York for the last time by liner on 15 December. She was forced to apply for a licence to the [[Solicitor General for England and Wales|Solicitor-General]] to become the first couple in modern times to hold a wedding at the Chapel of the [[Royal Hospital Chelsea]], which took place on 18 March 1954.<ref name=Telg9472666/>\n\n==Return to England==\nAfter working at Eton, her husband was Headmaster of [[The Leys School]] in Cambridge between 1958 and 1975, before moving to [[University College School, London]]. She played host to the rich and famous, often travelling abroad to raise funds for The Leys from parents and old boys. They invited the local dignitaries [[Edward Heath]] MP and the [[Katharine, Duchess of Kent|Duchess of Kent]] with the [[Prime Minister of Singapore]] to an open day. In 1961, the [[Queen Mother]] came to tea, and then again to open an extension to buildings in 1973.\n\nOn the day that [[Harold Wilson]] resigned in 1970, she invited Heath to view the cricket pitches, which was reciprocated by a visit to [[10 Downing Street|No.10]]. Other royalty continued to attend from Bahrain and Tonga. She promoted the school with her own brand of conservatism, taking care of mental health and epilepsy in the school. With Eton's help they started a boat club, spent time at [[Cliveden]] and in 1962 included among their friends, the Astors.<ref>Trumpington, p.162</ref> The Macmillan era was rounded off with a world tour to drum up school business.\n\nThe couple had one son, Adam Campbell Barker born on 31 August 1955. Adam was educated at [[King's School, Canterbury]] and [[Queens' College, Cambridge]]. He qualified as a [[solicitor]] and, later, as a [[barrister]]. He was married in 1985 to Elizabeth Mary, daughter of Eric Marsden OBE of Stourpaine Manor, Blandford.<ref name=Telg9472666/>\n\n==Conservative politics==\nSince 1945, Mother and Baby Homes (otherwise known as [[maternity home]]s) had been places for the poor to wean their offspring. She was appointed governor of the one in [[Cambridge]], and moved to Cambridge where her voluntary work continued.<ref>Trumpington, pp.177\u20138</ref> The United Cambridge Hospital Board, the Cambridge Social Services Committee, and the [[Museum of Cambridge|Cambridge Folk Museum]] all received her patronage. She was a member of the Rheumatism and Arthritis Association, which began serious research work on debilitation at Cambridge laboratories. She gained public notoriety for personally tackling{{dub|date=November 2018}} the 'Cambridge Rapist' in her own home, for whom the police had been searching for years without success; a burglar turned out to be the wanted felon masquerading as a door-to-door salesman calling himself MacFisheries.{{citation needed|date=November 2018}}\n\nIn 1963, she was elected as councillor for [[Trumpington, Cambridgeshire|Trumpington]] on [[Cambridge City Council]]. In 1971/2, she served as [[Mayor of Cambridge]] which she described as a \"[[wikt:folderol|folderol]]\". That office was followed by appointment to the Cambridge bench as a [[Justice of the Peace]] from 1972. She granted the Freedom of Cambridge to [[RAF Oakington]], revived the town's market, installed a travel centre, and built an entrance hall to the railway station. She opened the [[Elizabeth Way Bridge]] with former Conservative cabinet minister [[Rab Butler]], [[High Steward (academia)|High Steward of Cambridge University]]. She arranged to \"twin\" Cambridge with three other great university cities, [[Florence]], [[Heidelberg]] and [[Split, Croatia|Split]]. She raised funds for [[Addenbrooke's Hospital]] and the Indo-Pakistan War Relief Fund, and undertook a swimathon.\n\nBefore the local government and administration of justice re-organisation, it was usual for the upper classes to sit on the bench as a matter of [[nobless oblige|public duty]]. She re-entered politics in 1973, when she was elected to [[Cambridgeshire County Council]] for the Trumpington division but resigned in 1975 over the rapist scandal.<ref name=Debretts/>{{clarify|date=November 2018}} She sought election to [[Parliament of the United Kingdom|Parliament]], and reached the short list for the [[Isle of Ely (UK Parliament constituency)|Isle of Ely]] for the [[October 1974 United Kingdom general election|October 1974 election]].<ref name=Telg9472666/> (Dr [[Thomas Stuttaford]] was selected instead and lost to [[Clement Freud]].) That year marked a watershed in her political career. Stepping up a gear, she moved into a visibly national profile: her son was by now fully grown and starting a career. Continuing a gradual move up the career ladder into public life, Barker matured into a serious-minded public figure; she was appointed to the Board of Visitors of the women's gaol attached to [[HM Prison Pentonville|Pentonville Prison]] in London. She was one of the few who could get along well with the leader of her party, [[Margaret Thatcher]].<ref>Walker, Andy. [https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-27888144 \"Baroness Trumpington profile: From Lloyd George to the Lords\"]. ''[[BBC News]]'', 11 November 2014</ref>\n\nIn addition, the former councillor was appointed by the Labour government to the [[Mental Health Tribunal]], before [[care in the community|community care]] had been introduced. The following year, 1976, she was made a General Commissioner for Taxes, based on a competent showing with the city's finances. She served on various public bodies, including chair of the Air Transport Users Committee (1979\u201380).<ref name=Telg9472666/> One of the first questions she asked in the Lords was about improving the airmail service, in which area she was regarded an expert.<ref>Lord Trenchard said \"like Lady Trumpington's expert knowledge in relation to air mail\". HL Deb 30 April 1980 vol 408 cc1284-333 Retrieved 22 July 2016.</ref> The binding [[Official Secrets Act#United Kingdom|Official Secrets]] clause was repealed, privatisation followed, and profitability indexation restored to Air Mail services.<ref>{{cite web|df=dmy-all |url=http://hansard.millbanksystems.com/lords/1980/apr/30/post-office-services-1#S5LV0408P0_19800430_HOL_160|title=POST OFFICE SERVICES (Hansard, 30 April 1980)|website=hansard.millbanksystems.com}}</ref>\n\nHer interest in women's affairs became known for all the world to see when Thatcher became Prime Minister. Appointed as UK Representative to the [[UN Commission on the Status of Women]] it was her role to promote women's equality, marriage and divorce, healthcare, child-rearing, and human rights. She had an extensive address book in the United States; managing British interests on the Council in New York gave her a social profile that befitted her class status and ambition, but was nonetheless useful networking for the British Government.<ref>Burke's Peerage, 107th edition, vol.III.</ref> Belated recognition came from a Labour peeress:\n\n{{quote|On a different canvas, the noble Baroness, Lady Trumpington, then UK representative at the UN Commission on the Status of Women, helped to unite the international voice of women through her irresistible humour and sense of fun. It was good to be so involved in those days.<ref>{{cite web|df=dmy-all |url=http://hansard.millbanksystems.com/lords/2004/nov/23/address-in-reply-to-her-majestys-most#S5LV0667P0_20041123_HOL_68|title=Address in Reply to Her Majesty's Most Gracious Speech (Hansard, 23 November 2004)|website=hansard.millbanksystems.com}}</ref>}} Sent by Mrs Thatcher to Copenhagen, she headed a delegation to UK's first female ambassador, [[Anne Warburton]]. At the UN she crossed the floor to greet [[Suzanne Mubarak]], who made a brave speech for advancing peace in the Middle East.\n\nLady Trumpington was a steward of [[Folkestone Racecourse]] (1980\u201392).<ref name=Telg9472666/> In 1980, she was made an Honorary Fellow of [[Lucy Cavendish College]], Cambridge. She was a member of the Farmers\u2019 Club and Grillion's Club in London.<ref>Burke's 107th ed. (London 2003), vol.III, p.1949</ref>\n\n==Ministerial office from the Lords==\n{{more citations needed|section|date=January 2019}}\nIn almost her first debate she found herself on two sides of the same debate: discussing Clause no.23 amendment sponsored by Duke of Norfolk to Education Bill No. 2 1980.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://hansard.millbanksystems.com/lords/1980/mar/13/education-no-2-bill#S5LV0406P0_19800313_HOL_125|title=EDUCATION (No. 2) BILL (Hansard, 13 March 1980)|website=hansard.millbanksystems.com}}</ref> In June 1983, she joined the Lords [[Works of Art Committee]]. She became a resident expert on the committee, where she sat until 2010.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.parliament.uk/biographies/lords/baroness-trumpington/1820|title=Baroness Trumpington|website=UK Parliament}}</ref>\n\nOn leaving the UN post and entering the House of Lords, she was introduced as a [[Baroness-in-waiting]] from 1983 to 1985. Thatcher recognised her capabilities when she was given a ministerial post. Despite being in the Lords as [[Parliamentary Under-Secretary of State]] at the [[Department of Health and Social Security]] from 1985\u201387, during which time she smoked cigarettes, and in spite of a deep concern for women's mental health with numerous charities, she would ''in perpetuum'' champion the cause of smokers to do what they wanted.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://hansard.millbanksystems.com/lords/2004/dec/21/administration-and-works-committee#S5LV0667P0_20041221_HOL_153|title=Administration and Works Committee (Hansard, 21 December 2004)|website=hansard.millbanksystems.com}}</ref> A stubborn streak of wilful independence was typical of the Thatcherite in her, which she never lost up until her final ''verbatim'' speech in the Lords.<ref>Weds 15 March 2005,\n[http://hansard.millbanksystems.com/lords/2005/mar/09/smoking-in-public-places#S5LV0670P0_20050309_HOL_17 Hansard01]\nsee also: [http://parlipapers.chadwyck.co.uk/hansard/fullrec.do?area=hcpp&resultNum=1&entries=116&source=config6.cfg&queryId=../session/1469189082_22372&fulltexthits=106 Hansard HL Deb 09 March 2005 vol 670 cc727-9]</ref>\n\nMoving to the Ministry of Agriculture, which suited her temperament better than social security, at the height of the Thatcher boom period from 1987 to 1989, she was made [[Parliamentary Under-Secretary]]. She was promoted to number two at the ministry in 1989 when the Prime Minister was still creating [[hereditary peerage]]s; she valued her friendship and support. She continued until 1992, serving during John Major's administration as [[Minister of State]] at the [[Ministry of Agriculture, Fisheries and Food (United Kingdom)|Ministry of Agriculture, Fisheries and Food]], when at age 69 she was the oldest female minister ever.<ref name=Telg9472666/><ref name=Debretts/>\n\nHer last role was once again as a Baroness-in-waiting to the Queen<ref name=\":0\"/> from 1992\u201397, when a change of government ended her career. Acting in the capacity as a whip and a courtier, she felt compelled to attend at the bedside of [[Sally Mugabe]] in a London Hospital. She also received [[Mohammed Zahir Shah]], the last king of Afghanistan, on behalf of the Queen. On several occasions during the 1990s, Lady Trumpington became acquainted with the [[New Labour]] opposition leaders, [[Tony Blair]] and [[Gordon Brown]] at Court. She was one of the few officials on hand in 1990 to recognise [[Mongolian Revolution of 1990|the new State of Mongolia]], subsequently travelling to Ulan Bator to deal with KGB-backed Russian investors on a construction project.{{citation needed|date=January 2019}}\n\nThe [[Blair ministry|New Labour government]] therefore decided to appoint her an Extraordinary Baroness-in-Waiting from 1998, given her many years of experience at Court. During the Labour government, she was consistently on the side of traditionalists. She voted often in favour of [[university tuition fees]] and raising the cap to \u00a39,000; opposed constitutional reform, telling the Lords that she believed in the [[first past the post|first-past-the-post system]]; and against the ban on [[fox hunting]]. Lady Trumpington was broadly in favour of [[Brexit]], particularly the diminution of EU integration. She voted against the bill to make a referendum necessary to transfer powers back from EU to UK.<ref>{{cite web|df=dmy-all |url=https://www.theyworkforyou.com/peer/13538/baroness_trumpington|title=Baroness Trumpington - TheyWorkForYou|website=TheyWorkForYou}}</ref> Trumpington remained a principled opponent of soft measures on crime. Consistently supportive of tough measures, she was appointed Trustee of [[Crimestoppers]] in 2004. This tied in closely with ongoing visitations to [[Pentonville Prison]], as Crimestoppers' emphasis was specific to schoolchildren and youth offending. She opposed \"walking free\" and [[community sentencing]]; her disarming charm when discoursing about conditions in Britain's jails alerted the Lords perspective on the significance of public participation in [[crime reduction]] initiatives.<ref>{{cite web|df=dmy-all |url=http://hansard.millbanksystems.com/lords/2004/dec/08/crime-prevention#S5LV0667P0_20041208_HOL_343.|title=Crime Prevention (Hansard, 8 December 2004)|website=hansard.millbanksystems.com}}</ref>\n\nHer sense of order, propriety and taste got her into trouble: mocked by a Labour peeress for commenting on the drab and dishevelled appearance of the House of Lords, she more than once appeared a martinet for insisting on \"[[dress code]]\".<ref>Baroness Billingham HL Deb 23 November 2004 vol 667 cc5-20 Retrieved 22 July 2016.</ref> On another occasion she gave a [[V sign as an insult|V-sign]] to [[Tom King, Baron King of Bridgwater|Lord King of Bridgwater]] in the House of Lords, 10 November 2011 when he referred to her advanced age during a [[Remembrance Day]] debate.<ref name=Telg9472666/><ref name=\"theguardian.com\">[https://www.theguardian.com/media/mediamonkeyblog/2011/nov/14/lords-v-sign-king \"House of Lords' V-sign makes X-rated viewing\"], The Guardian (London), 14 November 2011.</ref>\n\nWhen she tried to debate the \"plight of rural veterinary practices\", the peeress pretended to be deaf: she had long railed against the most absurd forms of political correctness.{{Clarify|date=January 2019}} In 2000\u201301, she was made President of the [[South of England Show|South of England Agricultural Show]], taking the opportunity to promote animal health, a cause for which she had in 1995 been awarded an Honorary Membership of the [[British Veterinary Association]], in response to her work in that ministry.<ref>Trumpington, p. 210</ref> Declining rural practices was caused directly by the government's farming policies; the yawning gap between policy and practice exposed weaknesses in the EFRACOM report. She had initiated the debate on 24 June 2004, and was widely praised for so doing.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://hansard.millbanksystems.com/lords/2004/jun/24/veterinary-practices#S5LV0662P0_20040624_HOL_185|title=Veterinary Practices (Hansard, 24 June 2004)|website=hansard.millbanksystems.com}}</ref> Throughout her career, she was notable for having raised uncomfortable truths about topics most politicians have avoided, such as the plight of women in prisons, or the fate of single mothers with mental health issues.{{citation needed|date=January 2019}}\n\nIn December 2012, she acknowledged the campaign for the government to give official recognition to the work of [[Alan Turing]]. In a letter to the ''[[Daily Telegraph]]'', the signatories, including [[Stephen Hawking]], the physicist; [[Martin Rees, Baron Rees of Ludlow|Lord Rees]], the [[astronomer royal]]; and [[Paul Nurse|Sir Paul Nurse]], [[List of presidents of the Royal Society|the president of the Royal Society]], called on Prime Minister [[David Cameron]] to support [[Alan Turing#Government apology and pardon support|a pardon for Turing's 1952 conviction for homosexuality]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2013/jul/20/alan-turing-posthumous-pardon|title=Pardoning Alan Turing is a pointless exercise|author=Ben Summerskill|work=The Guardian|accessdate=3 January 2016}}</ref> Trumpington worked at Bletchley Park during the war at the same time as Turing, commenting only on his presence.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-2434273/Baroness-Trumpington-THAT-finger-gesture-scared-PM-dared-touch-up.html|title=Baroness Trumpington, THAT two-finger gesture and how she scared off PM who dared touch her up|date=27 September 2013|work=Mail Online|accessdate=3 January 2016}}</ref>\n\nShe retired from the House of Lords on 24 October 2017, one day after her 95th birthday.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.parliament.uk/biographies/lords/baroness-trumpington/1820|title=Baroness Trumpington|publisher=[[Parliament of the United Kingdom|UK Parliament]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Baroness Trumpington Retires|df=dmy-all |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/amp/uk-politics-41550627}}</ref>\n\n==Honours==\nTrumpington was appointed an [[National Order of Merit (France)|Officer of the National Order of Merit]] by the French Republic.<ref name=Debretts>{{cite web|url=http://www.debretts.com/people/biographies/browse/t/4080/Jean+Alys.aspx|title=The Rt Hon the Baroness Trumpington, DCVO, PC|publisher=[[Debrett's]]|accessdate=3 December 2012}}</ref> On 4 February 1980 she was created a [[life peer]], choosing the title Baroness Trumpington, of [[Sandwich, Kent|Sandwich]] in the [[County of Kent]].<ref name=Telg9472666/><ref>{{London Gazette|issue=48091|date=7 February 1980|page=1977}}</ref> She was appointed a [[Royal Victorian Order|Dame Commander of the Royal Victorian Order]] in 2005.<ref name=Telg9472666/><ref>{{London Gazette|issue=57665|date=11 June 2005|page=3|supp=y}}</ref> Leaving government she was granted an Honorary Fellowship of the [[Royal College of Pathologists]] (FRCPath). Two years later she was recognised for her voluntary activities as Honorary Associate of the Royal College of Volunteer Services (ARCVS).{{citation needed|date=December 2017}}\n\n==Media==\nAs a castaway on ''[[Desert Island Discs]]'' in 1990 she chose as her luxury item the [[Crown Jewels of the United Kingdom|Crown Jewels]] in order to maximise her chances of being rescued.<ref name=desertisland>{{cite web|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/radio4/features/desert-island-discs/castaway/2e3554a8|title=Desert island Discs}}</ref>\n\nIn 2011, she published a jaunty [[ghost-written]] memoir, ''Coming Up Trumps''. In the preface, she wrote she was persuaded by huge demands from her friends and colleagues to have an autobiography published.<ref>Jean Trumpington, Coming Up Trumps: A Memoir, London: Macmillan, 2011.<!-- ISSN/ISBN needed --></ref>\n\nOn 30 November 2012, Trumpington was a guest panellist on the BBC TV's satirical news quiz ''[[Have I Got News for You]]''; at the age of 90 she was the oldest guest to have appeared on the programme. In December 2013 she was a guest on [[BBC Three]] chat show ''[[Backchat (2013 TV series)|Backchat]]'' with [[Jack Whitehall|Jack]] and [[Michael Whitehall]]. In 2014 she was a guest judge in the finals of the ''[[Great British Menu]]''.\n\nAt the end of December 2017, she was [[List of Today programme guest editors|one of the guest editors]] for BBC Radio 4's prestigious [[Today programme|''Today'' programme]]. Topics she chose to highlight included her long-standing [[Prostitution in the United Kingdom#Current legal status|campaign to legalise brothels]]; [[Sangita Myska]] was tasked with interviewing a brothel keeper, a sex worker, and a woman who had escaped the sex industry. Another topic was living with incurable diseases such as [[Crohn's disease|Crohn's]]. [[John Humphrys]] interviewed her about her life and career, when she credited good luck for much of her success.\n<ref>{{cite web|publisher=BBC Radio 4|title=Today|date=29 December 2017|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b09jqtjx|accessdate=29 December 2017}}</ref>\n\nShe was referenced as suffering from the fictional 'Slimmels disease' in the spoof news and current affairs satire [[The Day Today]].\n\n==Later life and death==\nLady Trumpington was widowed in 1988.<ref name=Telg9472666/> In later interviews with ''The Guardian'' she described enjoying her grandchildren. She also enjoyed [[contract bridge]], [[needlepoint]] and [[horse racing]].<ref name=Debretts/>  In January 2010, while she was out, her flat in [[Battersea]] caught fire; her possessions were badly damaged.<ref name=Telg9472666/>\n\nShe died in her sleep on 26 November 2018. Her death was confirmed by her son, Adam Barker on [[Twitter]] later that night. He wrote: \"My mother passed away this afternoon in her sleep&nbsp;... she had a bloody good innings.\"<ref>https://www.shropshirestar.com/news/uk-news/2018/11/26/baroness-trumpington-bletchley-park-code-breaker-with-celebrated-v-sign-dies/</ref>\n\n==Arms==\n{{Infobox COA wide\n|image = [[File:Coronet of a British Baron.svg|centre|100px]] [[File:Arms of Jean Barker, Baroness Trumpington.svg|centre|200px]]\n|coronet = A [[Coronet|Coronet of a Baron]]\n|escutcheon = ''Gyronny of eight Ermine and Azure three Hedgehogs two and one Or.''<ref>{{cite web|df=dmy-all |url=http://www.cracroftspeerage.co.uk/online/content/lp1958%20t.htm?zoom_highlight=trumpington |title=Life Peerages - T |publisher=Cracroftspeerage.co.uk |date= |accessdate=2018-12-30}}</ref>\n|supporters =  Dexter: a Boxer Bitch; Sinister: a Bay Colt, both proper\n|motto = ''Gagne Tout Sans Atouts'' (\"Win all with no trumps\")\n|orders = [[Royal Victorian Order]]\n}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n'''Bibliography'''\n* {{cite book|first=Jean|last= Trumpington|title=Coming Up Trumps: A Memoir|location=London|publisher=Macmillan|date=2011|isbn=978-1-4472-5677-9}}\n\n==External links==\n{{wikisource|Barker, Jean, Baroness Trumpington}}\n{{wikiquote|Barker, Jean, Baroness Trumpington}}\n* {{cite news|df=dmy-all |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2014/apr/27/enigmatic-baroness-trumpington-bletchley-park-code-breaker|title= Enigmatic Baroness Trumpington|author= Cooke, Rachel|newspaper= [[The Guardian]]|date=27 April 2014 |accessdate= 12 January 2019}}\n* {{cite news|df=dmy-all |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-27888144|title= Baroness Trumpington profile: From Lloyd George to the Lords|date=11 November 2014 |work=[[BBC News]]|author=Walker, Andy|accessdate=12 January 2019}}\n* {{cite news|df=dmy-all |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/politics/9472666/Baroness-Trumpington-At-my-age-I-dont-give-a-damn-what-I-say.html|title= Baroness Trumpington: 'At my age I don\u2019t give a damn what I say'|date= 14 August 2012|work=[[The Daily Telegraph]] |author= Grice, Elizabeth|accessdate=12 January 2019}}\n* {{cite web|df=dmy-all |url=http://www.parliament.uk/biographies/lords/baroness-trumpington/1820|title= Baroness Trumpington|website=Parliament.uk |accessdate=7 July 2016}}\n* {{cite journal|df=dmy-all |url=http://jmg.bmj.com/content/24/4/235.full.pdf|title=Visit of Health Minister to Clinical Genetics Society |journal=[[Journal of Medical Genetics]] |year=1987 |volume=24 |pp=235\u2013249 |accessdate=22 July 2016}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Trumpington, Jean Barker, Baroness}}\n[[Category:1922 births]]\n[[Category:2018 deaths]]\n[[Category:Bletchley Park people]]\n[[Category:Bletchley Park women]]\n[[Category:Conservative Party (UK) Baronesses- and Lords-in-Waiting]]\n[[Category:Conservative Party (UK) life peers]]\n[[Category:Members of Cambridgeshire County Council]]\n[[Category:Dames Commander of the Royal Victorian Order]]\n[[Category:English autobiographers]]\n[[Category:English expatriates in the United States]]\n[[Category:English people of American descent]]\n[[Category:Female life peers]]\n[[Category:Mayors of Cambridge]]\n[[Category:Members of the Privy Council of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Officers of the National Order of Merit (France)]]\n[[Category:People from Trumpington]]\n[[Category:Women autobiographers]]\n[[Category:Women mayors of places in England]]\n[[Category:Socialites from London]]\n", 