{"title_page": "Conqueror's Blade", "text_new": "{{short description|Upcoming video game}}\n{{Infobox video game\n| title = Conqueror's Blade\n| developer = Booming Games<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.boominggames.com/|title=Booming Games|website=boominggames.com|language=en|access-date=2019-04-29}}</ref>\n| publisher = {{Unbulleted list|[[My.com]]<ref name=\"auto2\">{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/official_conqb/status/1024293735226650626|title=Conqueror's Blade EN on Twitter|website=twitter.com|language=en|access-date=2019-04-29}}</ref>|[[Mail.ru]]<ref name=\"auto1\">{{Cite web|url=https://cb.mail.ru/|title=Conqueror's Blade|website=cb.mail.ru|language=ru|access-date=2019-04-29}}</ref>}}\n| engine = CHAOS\n| platforms = [[Microsoft Windows]]\n| released = {{ubl|'''Windows'''|June 4, 2019 (Open Beta)|}}<ref name=\"auto\">{{Cite web|url=https://cb.my.com/en/news/152-early-access-and-open-beta-details-revealed|title=Conqueror's Blade|website=cb.my.com|language=en|access-date=2019-05-28}}</ref>\n| genre = [[Real-time tactics]], [[Massively multiplayer online game|MMO]]\n| modes = [[Single-player video game|Single-player]], [[Multiplayer video game|multiplayer]]\n}}\n\n'''Conqueror's Blade''' is an upcoming [[free-to-play]], [[Massively multiplayer online game|massively multiplayer online]] [[real-time tactics]] game developed by Chinese studio Booming Games, published by [[Mail.Ru Group|Mail.ru]] in Russia and [[My.com]] in Europe and North America, and due for release on [[Microsoft Windows]] in 2019.<ref name=\"auto\"/> It is set in an [[open world]] inspired by [[Middle Ages|medieval]] and [[Feudalism|feudal]] civilizations, and centers around [[Siege|siege combat]], commanding units in real-time, and seizing territory from other players in online battles.\nThe game is released for ages 12 and up.\n\n== Gameplay ==\nConqueror's Blade features [[turn-based strategy]] and [[real-time tactics]] gameplay in online battles, similar to the [[Total War (video game series)|Total War]] or [[Command & Conquer]] series. Players can directly take control of a warlord, who will issue orders to regiments that follow them into battle.\n\n=== Units and classes ===\nPlayers select a warlord from 10 available fighting classes, each with their own weapon specialization, and can customize the gender and appearance. Available weapons include the [[\u014cdachi|nodachi]], [[glaive]], [[Pollaxe|poleaxe]], [[Bow and arrow|bow]], and [[musket]]. This warlord can be controlled directly in combat and can be used to issue commands to different units on the battlefield and during sieges. Several units have been confirmed, including [[Polish hussars|Winged Hussars]], [[Tercio|Tercio Arquebusiers]], [[Cataphract|Cataphract Lancers]], and other units and fighting classes from different Eastern and Western civilizations.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://cb.my.com/en/about|title=Conqueror's Blade|website=cb.my.com|language=en|access-date=2019-04-29}}</ref>\n\n=== Siege Mode ===\nSeveral modes can be played, with the principal mode being the online Siege Mode with up to fifteen players on each team. Warlords can direct units to attack, follow, or take formation on the battlefield, and authentic siege weapons such as [[trebuchet]]s, [[cannon]]s, and [[battering ram]]s can be ordered to assault enemy fortifications.\n\n=== Houses ===\nPlayers can also form Houses with other players. This guild-like system allows players to form alliances to share resources and rewards, and team up to participate in larger battles and territory wars.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://cb.my.com/en/guilds|title=Conqueror's Blade|website=cb.my.com|language=en|access-date=2019-04-29}}</ref>\n\n== Development ==\nConqueror's Blade has been in development since 2013. It was originally known as War Rage<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://mmoculture.com/2017/06/conquerors-blade-netease-showcases-new-war-mmo-at-e3-2017/|title=MMO Culture|website=mmoculture.com|language=en|access-date=2019-04-29}}</ref> and was renamed Conqueror's Blade when it was first revealed to the public at [[E3 2017]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.boominggames.com/home/11.html|title=Booming Games|website=boominggames.com|language=en|access-date=2019-04-29}}</ref>\n\nConqueror's Blade is the first game developed by Booming Games, a Chinese development studio based in [[Hangzhou]], [[China]]. Several employees, including CEO Xi Wang, previously worked on the [[Halo (franchise)|Halo]] and [[Destiny (video game)|Destiny]] series at [[Bungie]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://wccftech.com/conquerors-blade-interview-mmo-war-game/|title=Wccftech.com|website=wccftech.com|language=en|access-date=2019-04-29}}</ref> Conqueror's Blade is also the first game to use the CHAOS engine, which was developed in-house at Booming Games.\n\n=== Business model ===\nConqueror's Blade is [[free-to-play]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://cb.my.com/en/about|title=Conqueror's Blade {{!}} Sign up for Beta|website=Conqueror's Blade|language=en|access-date=2019-04-29}}</ref> but will allow players to pay for certain in-game content. Founder's Packs are currently available that grant access to beta tests, along with other in-game content and items.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://cb.my.com/en/preorder|title=Conqueror's Blade {{!}} Sign up for Beta|website=Conqueror's Blade|language=en|access-date=2019-04-29}}</ref>\n\n== Release ==\nOn July 31, 2018, it was confirmed that [[My.com]] would publish the game in Europe and North America.<ref name=\"auto2\"/> [[Mail.ru]] will handle publishing duties in Russia.<ref name=\"auto1\"/>\n\nSeveral [[closed beta]] tests have been held for the game, with the most recent taking place in April 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://cb.my.com/en/news/127-the-open-weekend-is-over-an-extended-spring-mayhem-is-about-to-begin|title=Conqueror's Blade {{!}} Sign up for Beta|website=Conqueror's Blade|language=en|access-date=2019-04-29}}</ref> An [[open beta]] launch is planned for Spring 2019.\n\n== Reception ==\nConqueror's Blade received positive previews during its pre-release phases. [[Rock, Paper, Shotgun|Rock Paper Shotgun]] said the game was \"a hell of spectacle\", though criticized some of the grinding and 'level-gating'.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rockpapershotgun.com/2018/02/02/conquerors-blade-beta-review/|title=Siege warfare MMO Conqueror\u2019s Blade is Total War vs For Honor vs Planetside|last=Meer|first=Alec|date=2018-02-02|website=Rock, Paper, Shotgun|language=en-US|access-date=2019-04-29}}</ref> MMORPG.com said that the game showed \u201cglorious victory, brilliantly rendered by Booming\u2019s own CHAOS engine.\u201d<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mmorpg.com/conquerors-blade/previews/hands-on-preview-spilling-guts-never-looked-so-glorious-1000012906|title=Hands On Preview - Spilling Guts Never Looked So Glorious|website=mmorpg.com|language=en|access-date=2019-04-29}}</ref> WCCFtech praised the game's tutorial and claimed the game was \u201ceasy and accessible\u201d to new players.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://wccftech.com/conquerors-blade-preview-hands-on-and-more/|title=Conqueror\u2019s Blade Preview \u2013 Hands-on and More|website=wccftech.com|language=en|access-date=2019-04-29}}</ref> MMOBomb said that the siege battles were \u201cfun as all heck.\u201d<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mmobomb.com/features/clash-swords-hands-military-mash-conquerors-blade/|title=A Clash of Swords: Hands-on With Military Mash-up Conqueror\u2019s Blade|website=mmobomb.com|language=en|access-date=2019-04-29}}</ref>\n\n[[Jeuxvideo.com]] gave praise to the promise of the siege battles,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.jeuxvideo.com/preview/1000120/conqueror-s-blade-au-ceur-des-batailles-et-des-conquetes-medievales.htm|title=Conqueror's Blade : Au c\u0153ur des batailles et des conqu\u00eates m\u00e9di\u00e9vales|website=jeuxvideo.com|language=fr|access-date=2019-04-29}}</ref> with Gamestar.de similarly praising to the scale of battles, comparing the game to the [[Total War (video game series)|Total War series]], [[Mount & Blade]], and [[World of Warcraft]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gamestar.de/artikel/riesige-mittelalter-belagerungen-als-strategie-mmo-conquerors-blade-am-wochenende-kostenlos,3338319.html|title=Riesige Mittelalter-Belagerungen als Strategie-MMORPG - Conqueror's Blade am Wochenende kostenlos|website=gamestar.de|language=de|access-date=2019-04-29}}</ref> Mein-mmo.de favorably compared the scale of the game and its cinematic moments to films like [[Kingdom of Heaven (film)|Kingdom of Heaven]] and [[The Lord of the Rings (film series)|The Lord of the Rings trilogy]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://mein-mmo.de/taktische-action-spektakel-conquerors-blade-getestet/|title=Wir haben das taktische Action-Spektakel \u201eConqueror\u2018s Blade\u201c getestet|website=mein-mmo.de|language=de|access-date=2019-04-29}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n<!-- Inline citations added to your article will automatically display here. See en.wikipedia.org/wiki/WP:REFB for instructions on how to add citations. -->\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Upcoming video games]]\n[[Category:Massively multiplayer online games]]\n[[Category:Open world video games]]\n[[Category:Video games developed in China]]\n[[Category:Windows games]]\n[[Category:Windows-only games]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Upcoming video game}}\n{{Infobox video game\n| title = Conqueror's Blade\n| developer = Booming Games<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.boominggames.com/|title=Booming Games|website=boominggames.com|language=en|access-date=2019-04-29}}</ref>\n| publisher = {{Unbulleted list|[[My.com]]<ref name=\"auto2\">{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/official_conqb/status/1024293735226650626|title=Conqueror's Blade EN on Twitter|website=twitter.com|language=en|access-date=2019-04-29}}</ref>|[[Mail.ru]]<ref name=\"auto1\">{{Cite web|url=https://cb.mail.ru/|title=Conqueror's Blade|website=cb.mail.ru|language=ru|access-date=2019-04-29}}</ref>}}\n| engine = CHAOS\n| platforms = [[Microsoft Windows]]\n| released = {{ubl|'''Windows'''|June 4 2019 (Open Beta)|}}<ref name=\"auto\">{{Cite web|url=https://cb.my.com/en/news/152-early-access-and-open-beta-details-revealed|title=Conqueror's Blade|website=cb.my.com|language=en|access-date=2019-05-28}}</ref>\n| genre = [[Real-time tactics]], [[Massively multiplayer online game|MMO]]\n| modes = [[Single-player video game|Single-player]], [[Multiplayer video game|multiplayer]]\n}}\n\n'''Conqueror\u2019s Blade''' is an upcoming [[free-to-play]], [[Massively multiplayer online game|massively multiplayer online]] [[real-time tactics]] game developed by Chinese studio Booming Games, published by [[Mail.Ru Group|Mail.ru]] in Russia and [[My.com]] in Europe and North America, and due for release on [[Microsoft Windows]] in 2019.<ref name=\"auto\"/> It is set in an [[open world]] inspired by [[Middle Ages|medieval]] and [[Feudalism|feudal]] civilizations, and centers around [[Siege|siege combat]], commanding units in real-time, and seizing territory from other players in online battles.\nThe game is released for ages 12 and up.\n\n== Gameplay ==\nConqueror\u2019s Blade features [[turn-based strategy]] and [[real-time tactics]] gameplay in online battles, similar to the [[Total War (video game series)|Total War]] or [[Command & Conquer]] series. Players can directly take control of a warlord, who will issue orders to regiments that follow them into battle.\n\n=== Units and classes ===\nPlayers select a warlord from 10 available fighting classes, each with their own weapon specialization, and can customize the gender and appearance. Available weapons include the [[\u014cdachi|nodachi]], [[glaive]], [[Pollaxe|poleaxe]], [[Bow and arrow|bow]], and [[musket]]. This warlord can be controlled directly in combat and can be used to issue commands to different units on the battlefield and during sieges. Several units have been confirmed, including [[Polish hussars|Winged Hussars]], [[Tercio|Tercio Arquebusiers]], [[Cataphract|Cataphract Lancers]], and other units and fighting classes from different Eastern and Western civilizations.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://cb.my.com/en/about|title=Conqueror's Blade|website=cb.my.com|language=en|access-date=2019-04-29}}</ref>\n\n=== Siege Mode ===\nSeveral modes can be played, with the principal mode being the online Siege Mode with up to fifteen players on each team. Warlords can direct units to attack, follow, or take formation on the battlefield, and authentic siege weapons such as [[Trebuchet|trebuchets]], [[Cannon|cannons]], and [[Battering ram|battering rams]] can be ordered to assault enemy fortifications.\n\n=== Houses ===\nPlayers can also form Houses with other players. This guild-like system allows players to form alliances to share resources and rewards, and team up to participate in larger battles and territory wars.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://cb.my.com/en/guilds|title=Conqueror's Blade|website=cb.my.com|language=en|access-date=2019-04-29}}</ref>\n\n== Development ==\nConqueror's Blade has been in development since 2013. It was originally known as War Rage<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://mmoculture.com/2017/06/conquerors-blade-netease-showcases-new-war-mmo-at-e3-2017/|title=MMO Culture|website=mmoculture.com|language=en|access-date=2019-04-29}}</ref> and was renamed Conqueror\u2019s Blade when it was first revealed to the public at [[E3 2017]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.boominggames.com/home/11.html|title=Booming Games|website=boominggames.com|language=en|access-date=2019-04-29}}</ref>\n\nConqueror's Blade is the first game developed by Booming Games, a Chinese development studio based in [[Hangzhou]], [[China]]. Several employees, including CEO Xi Wang, previously worked on the [[Halo (franchise)|Halo]] and [[Destiny (video game)|Destiny]] series at [[Bungie]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://wccftech.com/conquerors-blade-interview-mmo-war-game/|title=Wccftech.com|website=wccftech.com|language=en|access-date=2019-04-29}}</ref> Conqueror\u2019s Blade is also the first game to use the CHAOS engine, which was developed in-house at Booming Games.\n\n=== Business model ===\nConqueror's Blade is [[free-to-play]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://cb.my.com/en/about|title=Conqueror's Blade {{!}} Sign up for Beta|website=Conqueror's Blade|language=en|access-date=2019-04-29}}</ref> but will allow players to pay for certain in-game content. Founder's Packs are currently available that grant access to beta tests, along with other in-game content and items.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://cb.my.com/en/preorder|title=Conqueror's Blade {{!}} Sign up for Beta|website=Conqueror's Blade|language=en|access-date=2019-04-29}}</ref>\n\n== Release ==\nOn July 31, 2018, it was confirmed that [[My.com]] would publish the game in Europe and North America.<ref name=\"auto2\"/> [[Mail.ru]] will handle publishing duties in Russia.<ref name=\"auto1\"/>\n\nSeveral [[closed beta]] tests have been held for the game, with the most recent taking place in April 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://cb.my.com/en/news/127-the-open-weekend-is-over-an-extended-spring-mayhem-is-about-to-begin|title=Conqueror's Blade {{!}} Sign up for Beta|website=Conqueror's Blade|language=en|access-date=2019-04-29}}</ref> An [[open beta]] launch is planned for Spring 2019.\n\n== Reception ==\nConqueror\u2019s Blade received positive previews during its pre-release phases. [[Rock, Paper, Shotgun|Rock Paper Shotgun]] said the game was \"a hell of spectacle\", though criticized some of the grinding and 'level-gating'.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rockpapershotgun.com/2018/02/02/conquerors-blade-beta-review/|title=Siege warfare MMO Conqueror\u2019s Blade is Total War vs For Honor vs Planetside|last=Meer|first=Alec|date=2018-02-02|website=Rock, Paper, Shotgun|language=en-US|access-date=2019-04-29}}</ref> MMORPG.com said that the game showed \u201cglorious victory, brilliantly rendered by Booming\u2019s own CHAOS engine.\u201d<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mmorpg.com/conquerors-blade/previews/hands-on-preview-spilling-guts-never-looked-so-glorious-1000012906|title=Hands On Preview - Spilling Guts Never Looked So Glorious|website=mmorpg.com|language=en|access-date=2019-04-29}}</ref> WCCFtech praised the game\u2019s tutorial and claimed the game was \u201ceasy and accessible\u201d to new players.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://wccftech.com/conquerors-blade-preview-hands-on-and-more/|title=Conqueror\u2019s Blade Preview \u2013 Hands-on and More|website=wccftech.com|language=en|access-date=2019-04-29}}</ref> MMOBomb said that the siege battles were \u201cfun as all heck.\u201d<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mmobomb.com/features/clash-swords-hands-military-mash-conquerors-blade/|title=A Clash of Swords: Hands-on With Military Mash-up Conqueror\u2019s Blade|website=mmobomb.com|language=en|access-date=2019-04-29}}</ref>\n\n[[Jeuxvideo.com]] gave praise to the promise of the siege battles,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.jeuxvideo.com/preview/1000120/conqueror-s-blade-au-ceur-des-batailles-et-des-conquetes-medievales.htm|title=Conqueror's Blade : Au c\u0153ur des batailles et des conqu\u00eates m\u00e9di\u00e9vales|website=jeuxvideo.com|language=fr|access-date=2019-04-29}}</ref> with Gamestar.de similarly praising to the scale of battles, comparing the game to the [[Total War (video game series)|Total War series]], [[Mount & Blade]], and [[World of Warcraft]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gamestar.de/artikel/riesige-mittelalter-belagerungen-als-strategie-mmo-conquerors-blade-am-wochenende-kostenlos,3338319.html|title=Riesige Mittelalter-Belagerungen als Strategie-MMORPG - Conqueror's Blade am Wochenende kostenlos|website=gamestar.de|language=de|access-date=2019-04-29}}</ref> Mein-mmo.de favorably compared the scale of the game and its cinematic moments to films like [[Kingdom of Heaven (film)|Kingdom of Heaven]] and [[The Lord of the Rings (film series)|The Lord of the Rings trilogy]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://mein-mmo.de/taktische-action-spektakel-conquerors-blade-getestet/|title=Wir haben das taktische Action-Spektakel \u201eConqueror\u2018s Blade\u201c getestet|website=mein-mmo.de|language=de|access-date=2019-04-29}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n<!-- Inline citations added to your article will automatically display here. See en.wikipedia.org/wiki/WP:REFB for instructions on how to add citations. -->\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Upcoming video games]]\n[[Category:Massively multiplayer online games]]\n[[Category:Open world video games]]\n[[Category:Video games developed in China]]\n[[Category:Windows games]]\n[[Category:Windows-only games]]\n", "name_user": "Nealbo", "label": "safe", "comment": "clean up,typo(s) fixed: \u2019s \u2192 's (6)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Conqueror%27s_Blade"}
{"title_page": "Bobby (1973 film)", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2015}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=November 2015}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = kos\n| image          = ker film film poster.jpg\n| caption        = Theatrical poster\n| director       = [[khisrow]]\n| producer       = Raj Kapoor\n| writer         = [[Jainendra Jain (screenwriter)|Jainendra Jain]] (dialogue)\n| screenplay     = [[Khwaja Ahmad Abbas]]<br />V. P. Sathe\n| story          = Khwaja Ahmad Abbas\n| starring       = [[Rishi Kapoor]]<br>[[Dimple Kapadia]]<br>[[Prem Nath]]<br>[[Pran (actor)|Pran]]\n| music          = [[Laxmikant\u2013Pyarelal]]\n| cinematography = [[Radhu Karmakar]]\n| editing        = Raj Kapoor\n| studio         = [[R.K. Films]]\n| distributor    = R.K. Films\n| released       = {{start date|df=yes|1973|9|28}}\n| runtime        = 169 minutes\n| country        = India\n| language       = [[Hindustani language|Hindustani]]<ref name=\"Dwyer\">{{cite book|last=Dwyer|first=Rachel|authorlink=Rachel Dwyer|title=Filming the Gods: Religion and Indian Cinema|date=2006|publisher=[[Routledge]]|isbn=9781134380701|page=106|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ZsKR1RKoJKUC&pg=PA106}}</ref>\n| budget         = \n| gross          = {{Estimation}} {{INR|30 [[crore]]}}<ref name=\"hindustantimes\"/><br> \n}}\n'''''Bobby''''' is a [[List of Bollywood films of 1973|1973]] Indian [[Musical film|musical]] [[romance film]], produced and directed by [[Raj Kapoor]], and written by [[Khwaja Ahmad Abbas]]. The film stars Raj Kapoor's son, [[Rishi Kapoor]], in his first leading role, opposite [[Dimple Kapadia]] in her debut role.\n\nThe film became a blockbuster, the top-grossing Indian hit of 1973,<ref name=\"boi73\">{{cite web |url=http://boxofficeindia.com/showProd.php?itemCat=179&catName=MTk3Mw==/1973.htm |title=Box Office 1973 |publisher=Boxofficeindia.com |accessdate=2011-06-01 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110721044326/http://boxofficeindia.com/showProd.php?itemCat=179&catName=MTk3Mw%3D%3D%2F1973.htm |archivedate=21 July 2011 |df=dmy }}</ref> the second-top-grossing hit of the 1970s at the Indian box office,<ref name=\"boi70s\">{{cite web|url=http://boxofficeindia.com/showProd.php?itemCat=124&catName=MTk3MC0xOTc5 |title=Top Earners 1970-1979 |publisher=Boxofficeindia.com |accessdate=2011-06-01 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131014062240/http://boxofficeindia.com/showProd.php?itemCat=124&catName=MTk3MC0xOTc5 |archivedate=14 October 2013 |df=dmy }}</ref> and one of the top 20 highest-grossing Indian films of all time (when adjusted for inflation).<ref name=\"gold3\"/> It also became an overseas blockbuster in the [[Soviet Union]], where it drew an audience of 62.6 million viewers,<ref name=\"soviet\"/> making it one of the top 20 biggest box office hits of all time in the [[Soviet Union]].<ref name=\"soviet-foreign\"/><ref name=\"soviet-domestic\"/> \n\nThe film became a trend-setter. It was wildly popular and widely imitated. It introduced to Bollywood the genre of teenage romance with a rich-versus-poor clash as a backdrop. Numerous films in the following years and decades were inspired by this plot. ''Indiatimes Movies'' ranks ''Bobby'' amongst the 'Top 25 Must See Bollywood Films'.<ref>{{Cite news |author=Kanwar, Rachna |title=25 Must See Bollywood Movies |date=3 October 2005 |url=http://movies.indiatimes.com/Special_Features/25_Must_See_Bollywood_Movies/articleshow/msid-1250837,curpg-11.cms |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071015033800/http://movies.indiatimes.com/Special_Features/25_Must_See_Bollywood_Movies/articleshow/msid-1250837%2Ccurpg-11.cms |url-status=dead |archive-date=15 October 2007 |publisher=Indiatimes movies |accessdate=2010-11-08 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n== Plot ==\nThe story is about the love between two [[Mumbai]] teenagers of different classes\u2014Raj Nath ([[Rishi Kapoor]]), the son of a rich businessman Mr. Nath (played by [[Pran (actor)|Pran]]), and Bobby Braganza ([[Dimple Kapadia]]), the daughter of a poor [[Goans|Goan]] Christian fisherman Jack Braganza (played by [[Prem Nath]]).\n\nRaj returns from his boarding school. Upon his return, his parents throw a party to celebrate his birthday. His governess as a child Mrs. Braganza comes to wish him with her granddaughter Bobby, whom Raj notices among the crowds attending his party. Mrs. Nath (played by [[Sonia Sahni]]) ignores Mrs. Braganza, which leads her to leave the party with her granddaughter in a rush.\n\nRaj opens his gifts the next day and finds Mrs. Braganza's gift, so he decides to go and meet her. Reaching there, her granddaughter Bobby opens the door for him, and it is love at first sight for him. During that visit, he mixes his book with Bobby's, so he goes to meet her at the library to exchange the books, and from that, both start their friendship. Raj and Bobby decide to go to see a movie but find out it is a full house. Then Raj gets an idea to go to a party. At the party, Bobby sees Raj talking to Nima (played by [[Aruna Irani]]) privately and thinks he is in love with her. As the story progresses, Raj realises that his relationship with the daughter of a poor fisherman is not taken kindly by his eccentric father. Upon Raj's insistence, Mr. Nath invites Jack Braganza to initiate talks of Raj and Bobby's wedding. But instead, Mr. Nath insults him and accuses Jack of using his daughter's beauty and charm to trap Raj for his money. He later offers Jack cash to stop Bobby from seeing Raj. Jack feels highly humiliated by this accusation and reciprocates by insulting Mr. Nath. Their talk enters a deadlock and spells doom for Raj and Bobby's tender love.\n\nMr. Nath engages Raj to a mentally challenged wealthy girl, Alka ([[Farida Jalal]]), to establish business ties with her rich father. But Raj runs away from home in order to unite with Bobby. They run away together. Mr. Nath advertises a reward for anyone who can help find his son. Prem Chopra ([[Prem Chopra]]) decides that he wants the money, and he and his goons kidnap Raj and Bobby. When they try to escape, Prem starts beating Raj. Mr. Nath and the police come to help, and they find Jack already there attempting to help Raj. Raj and Bobby run away from their fathers and jump over a waterfall. Mr. Nath and Jack jump into the water after them. Mr. Nath rescues Bobby, while Jack rescues Raj.\n\nThey realise that they love their children very much and don't want to stand in the way of their happiness. They accept each other's kids as their own and give their blessings to the union.\n\n== Cast ==\n* [[Rishi Kapoor]] as Raj Nath\n* [[Dimple Kapadia]] as Bobby Braganza\n* [[Prem Nath]] as Jack Braganza\n* [[Durga Khote]] as Mrs. Braganza\n* [[Pran (actor)|Pran]] as Mr. Nath\n* [[Sonia Sahni]] as Mrs. Sushma Nath\n* [[Aruna Irani]] as Nima\n* [[Prem Chopra]] as Prem Chopra\n* [[Farida Jalal]] as Alka 'Nikki' Sharma\n* [[Pinchoo Kapoor]] as Mr. Sharma\n* Raj Rani as Mrs. Sharma\n* [[Jagdish Raj]] as Police Inspector\n* [[Shashi Kiran]] as Shyam (Raj's college-mate)\n* [[Piloo J. Wadia]] as Mrs. Pestonji\n\n[[Raj Kapoor]] launched his second son [[Rishi Kapoor]] in this film; he wanted a new heroine to complement the young love story. [[Dimple Kapadia]] and [[Neetu Singh]] were auditioned for the role of Bobby Braganza, but Dimple was finally selected; meanwhile, Rishi Kapoor and Neetu Singh did many films together later on and became one of cinema's best screen couples and later crowned their relationship with marriage.\n\n==Production==\nIn an interview in 2012, [[Rishi Kapoor]] stated, \"There was a misconception that the film was made to launch me as an actor. The film was actually made to pay the debts of ''[[Mera Naam Joker]]''. Dad wanted to make a teenage love story and he did not have money to cast [[Rajesh Khanna]] in the film\".<ref name=\"dnaindia.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.dnaindia.com/entertainment/report_proud-of-ranbir-s-choice-of-roles-rishi-kapoor_1741229|title=Proud of Ranbir's choice of roles: Rishi Kapoor - Latest News & Updates at Daily News & Analysis|date=15 September 2012|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n===Filming===\nSome scenes were shot in [[Gulmarg]]. One scene was shot in a hut in Gulmarg, which became famous as the 'Bobby Hut'.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://movies.ndtv.com/bollywood/shah-rukh-khan-ek-kamre-mein-band-in-kashmir-262823 |title=Shah Rukh Khan ek kamre mein band in Kashmir |access-date=28 February 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140404062106/http://movies.ndtv.com/bollywood/shah-rukh-khan-ek-kamre-mein-band-in-kashmir-262823 |archive-date=4 April 2014 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>[http://www.kashmirfirst.com/articles/tourism/110301-the-gulmarg-nostalgia-10.htm The Gulmarg Nostalgia-X (Bollywood in Gulmarg-II!)]</ref> A few scenes towards the end of the movie were shot on Pune-Solapur highway near [[Loni Kalbhor]] where Raj Kapoor owned a farm.\n==Russia success==\nIt released in [[Russia|Russian Federation]] in 1975. It created amaze in [[Russian cinema]].\n\n==[[Russia|Russian Federation]] success==\nIt created havoc in [[Russian cinema]]. So it was released in Russia as a result in 1975 in [[Russian language|Russian]] and [[English language|English]]. It was one of most successful foreign films produced in Russian Federation\n\n== Soundtrack ==\nMusic by was composed by the [[Laxmikant\u2013Pyarelal|Laxmikant-Pyarelal]] Duo.The Lyrics were Penned by [[Anand Bakshi]], [[Rajkavi Inderjeet Singh Tulsi|Inderjeet Singh Tulsi]], and [[Vithalbhai Patel (lyricist)|Vithalbhai Patel]]. Lyrics penned by Anand Bakshi except where noted...Music became an evergreen hit.\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|- style=\"background:#ccc; text-align:center;\"\n! Song !! Singer(s)!! Notes\n|-\n|\"Ae Ae Ae Phansa\"\n|[[Lata Mangeshkar]]\n|Picturized on [[Aruna Irani]]\n|-\n|\"Ankhiyon Ko Rahne De\"\n|[[Lata Mangeshkar]]\n|Based on the song \"Ankhiyan nu rehen de\" by [[Reshma]]{{citation needed|reason=Your explanation here|date=February 2015}}\n|-\n|\"Beshak Mandir Masjid\"\n|[[Narendra Chanchal]]\nLyrics by Raj Kavi Inderjeet Singh Tulsi\n|\n|-\n|\"Hum Tum Ek Kamre Mein Band Ho\"\n|[[Lata Mangeshkar]] and [[Shailendra Singh (singer)|Shailendra Singh]]\n|\n|-\n|\"Jhoot Bole Kauva Kate\"\n|[[Lata Mangeshkar]] and Shailendra Singh\n|Picturized on [[Rishi Kapoor]] and [[Dimple Kapadia]] in a village dance setting.\n|-\n|\"Main Shayar To Nahin\"\n|Shailendra Singh\n|Picturised on Rishi Kapoor. The song was reused and picturised again on him in the 2004 film ''[[Hum Tum]]''.\n|-\n|\"Mujhe Kuchh Kahna Hai\"\n|[[Lata Mangeshkar]] and Shailendra Singh\n|\n|-\n|\"Na Mangun Sona Chandi\"\n|[[Manna Dey]] and Shailendra Singh\nLyrics by :Vithalbhai Patel\n|\n|}\n\n== Box office ==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"  style=\"float:right; width:45%; text-align:center;\"\n|+ Worldwide gross ({{estimation}})\n|-\n! Territory\n! Gross revenue\n! Adjusted gross\n! Footfalls\n|-\n| [[List of highest-grossing films in India|Domestic (India)]]\n| {{INR|11 [[crore]]|link=yes}}<ref name=\"boi73\"/> ({{US$|14.21 million|link=yes}}){{#tag:ref|7.742 [[Indian rupee]]s per [[US dollar]] in 1973<ref>http://fx.sauder.ubc.ca/etc/USDpages.pdf#page=3</ref>|group=n}}\n| [[Bollywood 100 Crore Club|{{INRConvert|{{Inflation|IN|398|2011}}|c}}]]{{#tag:ref|{{INR}}398 crore in 2011<ref name=\"gold70s\"/><ref name=\"gold3\"/>}}\n| {{#expr:110/(1.84*0.71+2.59*0.29) round 1}}{{nbsp}}million<ref name=\"mittal\">{{cite book |last1=Mittal |first1=Ashok |title=Cinema Industry in India: Pricing and Taxation |date=1995 |publisher=Indus Publishing |isbn=9788173870231 |pages=71 & 77 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=RJVodLc6NgoC&pg=PA77}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[List of highest-grossing Indian films in overseas markets|Overseas]] ([[List of Soviet films of the year by ticket sales|Soviet Union]])\n| 15.65{{nbsp}}million [[Soviet ruble|\u0440\u0443\u0431]]{{#tag:ref|62.6 million tickets sold,<ref name=\"soviet\"/> average ticket price of 25 [[Soviet ruble|kopecks]]<ref>[https://is.muni.cz/el/1421/podzim2015/FAV291/um/Roth-Ey-Moscow_Prime_Time.pdf#page=7 ''Moscow Prime Time: How the Soviet Union Built the Media Empire that Lost the Cultural Cold War'', page 48], [[Cornell University Press]], 2011</ref>|group=n}} {{ndash}} US$21.44{{nbsp}}million{{#tag:ref|0.73 [[Soviet ruble]]s per US dollar in 1975<ref>Archive of Bank of Russia http://cbr.ru/currency_base/OldDataFiles/USD.xls</ref>|group=n|name=RubleUSD}} ({{INR}}19.24{{nbsp}}crore){{#tag:ref|8.973 Indian rupees per US dollar in 1975<ref>https://www.rbi.org.in/scripts/PublicationsView.aspx?id=15268</ref>|group=n}}\n| US${{Inflation|US|21.44|1975}}{{nbsp}}million ({{INR}}638{{nbsp}}crore)<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.ofx.com/en-gb/forex-news/historical-exchange-rates/yearly-average-rates/ |title=67.175856 INR per USD in 2016 |access-date=18 June 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170713183556/https://www.ofx.com/en-gb/forex-news/historical-exchange-rates/yearly-average-rates/ |archive-date=13 July 2017 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n| 62.6{{nbsp}}million<ref name=\"soviet\"/>\n|-\n! [[List of highest-grossing Indian films|Worldwide]]\n! {{INR|{{#expr:11+19.24}} crore}} ({{US$|{{#expr:300/7.74 round 0}} million}})<ref name=\"hindustantimes\">{{cite news |title=On Independence Day, here are the most successful Indian movies of every decade since 1947 |url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/bollywood/on-independence-day-here-are-the-most-successful-indian-movies-of-every-decade-since-1947/story-EIf9tdhbWfO38hftOSwQIM.html |work=[[Hindustan Times]] |date=15 August 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Official exchange rate (LCU per US$, period average) |url=https://data.worldbank.org/indicator/PA.NUS.FCRF?end=1973&locations=IN&start=1972 |website=[[World Bank]] |year=1973 |accessdate=13 December 2018}}</ref>\n! [[Bollywood 1000 Crore Club|{{INR|{{#expr:574+638}} crore}}]] ({{US$|{{#expr:89+95}} million}})\n! {{#expr:53.5+62.6 round 0}}{{nbsp}}million\n|}\n\nIn India, ''Bobby'' was the highest-grossing film of 1973, earning [[Indian rupee|{{INR}}]]11 [[crore]].<ref name=\"boi73\"/> It was also the second-highest-grossing film at the Indian box office in the 1970s, second only to ''[[Sholay]]'' (1975).<ref name=\"boi70s\"/> Adjusted for inflation, it grossed {{INR}}398 crore in 2011 value,<ref name=\"gold70s\">[http://boxofficeindia.co.in/worth-their-weight-in-gold-70s/ Worth Their Weight In Gold! (70's)] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171022033244/http://boxofficeindia.co.in/worth-their-weight-in-gold-70s/# |date=22 October 2017 }}, ''[[Box Office India]]'', 3 November 2011</ref> equivalent to {{INRConvert|{{Inflation|IN|398|2011}}|c}} in 2016 value. As of 2011, it is one of the top 20 highest-grossing films of all time in India.<ref name=\"gold3\">[http://boxofficeindia.co.in/top-50-film-of-last-50-years/ Top 50 Film of Last 50 Years] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111104181418/http://boxofficeindia.co.in/top-50-film-of-last-50-years/# |date=4 November 2011 }}, ''[[Box Office India]]'', 3 November 2011</ref>\n\nOverseas, ''Bobby'' was very successful in the [[Soviet Union]] when it released there in 1975, due to Raj Kapoor's popularity in the country. ''Bobby'' drew 62.6{{nbsp}}million admissions at the Soviet box office, making it the second-best-selling film on the [[List of Soviet films of the year by ticket sales|Soviet box office charts]] in 1975,<ref name=\"soviet\">[https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=cpoLAQAAMAAJ ''Indian Films in Soviet Cinemas: The Culture of Movie-going After Stalin''], page 89, [[Indiana University Press]], 2005</ref> the most popular [[Indian film]] of the 1970s, the second-biggest foreign hit of the decade,<ref name=\"soviet-foreign\">{{cite web|url=http://kinanet.livejournal.com/13882.html|title=\u0417\u0430\u0440\u0443\u0431\u0435\u0436\u043d\u044b\u0435 \u0444\u0438\u043b\u044c\u043c\u044b \u0432 \u0441\u043e\u0432\u0435\u0442\u0441\u043a\u043e\u043c \u043a\u0438\u043d\u043e\u043f\u0440\u043e\u043a\u0430\u0442\u0435|author=Sergey Kudryavtsev|author-link=Sergey Kudryavtsev (film critic)}}</ref> the sixth-biggest box office hit of the decade,<ref name=\"soviet-foreign\"/><ref name=\"soviet-domestic\">{{cite web|url=http://kinanet.livejournal.com/14172.html|title=\u041e\u0442\u0435\u0447\u0435\u0441\u0442\u0432\u0435\u043d\u043d\u044b\u0435 \u0444\u0438\u043b\u044c\u043c\u044b \u0432 \u0441\u043e\u0432\u0435\u0442\u0441\u043a\u043e\u043c \u043a\u0438\u043d\u043e\u043f\u0440\u043e\u043a\u0430\u0442\u0435|author=Sergey Kudryavtsev|author-link=Sergey Kudryavtsev (film critic)}}</ref> the second-most-viewed Indian film of all time (after Raj Kapoor's ''[[Awaara]]''), the sixth-biggest foreign hit of all time,<ref name=\"soviet-foreign\"/> and one of the top 20 biggest box office hits of all time.<ref name=\"soviet-foreign\"/><ref name=\"soviet-domestic\"/> The film's success launched Rishi Kapoor into an overnight movie star in the Soviet Union,<ref>[https://is.muni.cz/el/1421/podzim2015/FAV291/um/Roth-Ey-Moscow_Prime_Time.pdf#page=4 ''Moscow Prime Time: How the Soviet Union Built the Media Empire that Lost the Cultural Cold War'', page 43], [[Cornell University Press]], 2011</ref> much like ''Awaara'' had done for his father Raj Kapoor.\n\n== Awards ==\n;[[21st Filmfare Awards]]\n* [[Filmfare Award for Best Actor|Best Actor]] \u2013 [[Rishi Kapoor]] (He later confessed that he bought the award for \u20b9 30000)\n* [[Filmfare Award for Best Actress|Best Actress]] \u2013 [[Dimple Kapadia]] (shared with [[Jaya Bhaduri]] for ''[[Abhimaan (1973 film)|Abhimaan]]'')\n* [[Filmfare Award for Best Male Playback Singer|Best Male Playback Singer]] \u2013 [[Narendra Chanchal]] for \"Beshak Mandir Masjid\"\n* [[Filmfare Award for Best Art Direction|Best Art Direction]] \u2013 A. Rangaraj\n* [[Filmfare Award for Best Sound Design|Best Sound Design]] \u2013 Allauddin Khan Qureshi\n\n;Nominations\n* [[Filmfare Award for Best Film|Best Film]] \u2013 [[Raj Kapoor]]\n* [[Filmfare Award for Best Director|Best Director]] \u2013 Raj Kapoor\n* [[Filmfare Award for Best Supporting Actor|Best Supporting Actor]] \u2013 [[Prem Nath]]\n* [[Filmfare Award for Best Supporting Actress|Best Supporting Actress]] \u2013 [[Aruna Irani]]\n* [[Filmfare Award for Best Music Director|Best Music Director]] \u2013 [[Laxmikant Pyarelal]]\n* [[Filmfare Award for Best Lyricist|Best Lyricist]] \u2013 [[Anand Bakshi]] for \"Hum Tum Ek Kamre Mein\"\n* Best Lyricist \u2013 Anand Bakshi for \"Main Shayer To Nahin\"\n* Best Lyricist \u2013 [[Vitthalbhai Patel]] for \"Jhoot Bole Kava Kate\"\n* Best Male Playback Singer \u2013 [[Shailender Singh]] for the song \"Main Shayar to Nahin\"\n<ref>{{cite web|url=http://deep750.googlepages.com/FilmfareAwards.pdf |title=1st Filmfare Awards 1953 |publisher=Deep750.googlepages.com |date= |accessdate=2011-06-01}}</ref>\n\n; [[Bengal Film Journalists' Association Awards|BFJA]] Awards\n* Best Male Playback Singer (Hindi Section) \u2013 [[Shailender Singh]]\n* BFJA Award for Best Audiographer (Hindi Section) \u2013 Alauddin Khan Qureshi<ref>[http://www.bfjaawards.com/legacy/pastwin/197437.htm 69th & 70th Annual Hero Honda BFJA Awards 2007] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080422070342/http://www.bfjaawards.com/legacy/pastwin/197437.htm |date=22 April 2008 }}</ref>\n\n==Controversy==\nIn his 2017 autobiography ''Khullam Khulla: Rishi Kapoor Uncensored'', [[Rishi Kapoor]] revealed that he paid someone {{INRConvert|30000|year=1974}} to win him the [[Filmfare Award for Best Actor|Best Actor]] award for ''Bobby'' at the [[21st Filmfare Awards]], beating [[Amitabh Bachchan]]'s performance for ''[[Zanjeer (1973 film)|Zanjeer]]''. However, he was not certain if the person he paid actually had connections to the Filmfare committee, or if he was just a fraud.<ref>{{cite news |title=Uncensored: Rishi Kapoor reveals *exactly* why he bought an award for Bobby |url=https://www.indiatoday.in/movies/celebrities/story/rishi-kapoor-reveals-bought-award-bobby-khullam-khulla-955884-2017-01-19 |work=[[India Today]] |date=19 January 2017}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n*[[100 Crore Club]]\n*[[List of Soviet films of the year by ticket sales]]\n\n== Notes ==\n{{reflist|group=n}}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{IMDb title|title=Bobby}}\n* {{AllRovi movie|title=Bobby}}\n* {{Rotten-tomatoes|1128675_bobby|title=Bobby}}\n\n{{Raj Kapoor}}\n{{K. A. Abbas}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bobby (1973 Film)}}\n[[Category:1973 films]]\n[[Category:1970s Hindi-language films]]\n[[Category:Urdu-language films]]\n[[Category:Indian films]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Raj Kapoor]]\n[[Category:Indian romantic musical films]]\n[[Category:1970s romantic musical films]]\n[[Category:Indian teen films]]\n[[Category:Films scored by Laxmikant\u2013Pyarelal]]\n[[Category:R. K. Films films]]\n[[Category:Indian interfaith romance films]]\n[[Category:Films with screenplays by Khwaja Ahmad Abbas]]\n[[Category:1970s teen romance films]]\n[[Category:Films set in Mumbai]]\n[[Category:Films set in Jammu and Kashmir]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Mumbai]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Jammu and Kashmir]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2015}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=November 2015}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Bobby\n| image          = Bobby film poster.jpg\n| caption        = Theatrical poster\n| director       = [[Raj Kapoor]]\n| producer       = Raj Kapoor\n| writer         = [[Jainendra Jain (screenwriter)|Jainendra Jain]] (dialogue)\n| screenplay     = [[Khwaja Ahmad Abbas]]<br />V. P. Sathe\n| story          = Khwaja Ahmad Abbas\n| starring       = [[Rishi Kapoor]]<br>[[Dimple Kapadia]]<br>[[Prem Nath]]<br>[[Pran (actor)|Pran]]\n| music          = [[Laxmikant\u2013Pyarelal]]\n| cinematography = [[Radhu Karmakar]]\n| editing        = Raj Kapoor\n| studio         = [[R.K. Films]]\n| distributor    = R.K. Films\n| released       = {{start date|df=yes|1973|9|28}}\n| runtime        = 169 minutes\n| country        = India\n| language       = [[Hindustani language|Hindustani]]<ref name=\"Dwyer\">{{cite book|last=Dwyer|first=Rachel|authorlink=Rachel Dwyer|title=Filming the Gods: Religion and Indian Cinema|date=2006|publisher=[[Routledge]]|isbn=9781134380701|page=106|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ZsKR1RKoJKUC&pg=PA106}}</ref>\n| budget         = \n| gross          = {{Estimation}} {{INR|30 [[crore]]}}<ref name=\"hindustantimes\"/><br> \n}}\n'''''Bobby''''' is a [[List of Bollywood films of 1973|1973]] Indian [[Musical film|musical]] [[romance film]], produced and directed by [[Raj Kapoor]], and written by [[Khwaja Ahmad Abbas]]. The film stars Raj Kapoor's son, [[Rishi Kapoor]], in his first leading role, opposite [[Dimple Kapadia]] in her debut role.\n\nThe film became a blockbuster, the top-grossing Indian hit of 1973,<ref name=\"boi73\">{{cite web |url=http://boxofficeindia.com/showProd.php?itemCat=179&catName=MTk3Mw==/1973.htm |title=Box Office 1973 |publisher=Boxofficeindia.com |accessdate=2011-06-01 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110721044326/http://boxofficeindia.com/showProd.php?itemCat=179&catName=MTk3Mw%3D%3D%2F1973.htm |archivedate=21 July 2011 |df=dmy }}</ref> the second-top-grossing hit of the 1970s at the Indian box office,<ref name=\"boi70s\">{{cite web|url=http://boxofficeindia.com/showProd.php?itemCat=124&catName=MTk3MC0xOTc5 |title=Top Earners 1970-1979 |publisher=Boxofficeindia.com |accessdate=2011-06-01 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131014062240/http://boxofficeindia.com/showProd.php?itemCat=124&catName=MTk3MC0xOTc5 |archivedate=14 October 2013 |df=dmy }}</ref> and one of the top 20 highest-grossing Indian films of all time (when adjusted for inflation).<ref name=\"gold3\"/> It also became an overseas blockbuster in the [[Soviet Union]], where it drew an audience of 62.6 million viewers,<ref name=\"soviet\"/> making it one of the top 20 biggest box office hits of all time in the [[Soviet Union]].<ref name=\"soviet-foreign\"/><ref name=\"soviet-domestic\"/> \n\nThe film became a trend-setter. It was wildly popular and widely imitated. It introduced to Bollywood the genre of teenage romance with a rich-versus-poor clash as a backdrop. Numerous films in the following years and decades were inspired by this plot. ''Indiatimes Movies'' ranks ''Bobby'' amongst the 'Top 25 Must See Bollywood Films'.<ref>{{Cite news |author=Kanwar, Rachna |title=25 Must See Bollywood Movies |date=3 October 2005 |url=http://movies.indiatimes.com/Special_Features/25_Must_See_Bollywood_Movies/articleshow/msid-1250837,curpg-11.cms |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071015033800/http://movies.indiatimes.com/Special_Features/25_Must_See_Bollywood_Movies/articleshow/msid-1250837%2Ccurpg-11.cms |url-status=dead |archive-date=15 October 2007 |publisher=Indiatimes movies |accessdate=2010-11-08 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n== Plot ==\nThe story is about the love between two [[Mumbai]] teenagers of different classes\u2014Raj Nath ([[Rishi Kapoor]]), the son of a rich businessman Mr. Nath (played by [[Pran (actor)|Pran]]), and Bobby Braganza ([[Dimple Kapadia]]), the daughter of a poor [[Goans|Goan]] Christian fisherman Jack Braganza (played by [[Prem Nath]]).\n\nRaj returns from his boarding school. Upon his return, his parents throw a party to celebrate his birthday. His governess as a child Mrs. Braganza comes to wish him with her granddaughter Bobby, whom Raj notices among the crowds attending his party. Mrs. Nath (played by [[Sonia Sahni]]) ignores Mrs. Braganza, which leads her to leave the party with her granddaughter in a rush.\n\nRaj opens his gifts the next day and finds Mrs. Braganza's gift, so he decides to go and meet her. Reaching there, her granddaughter Bobby opens the door for him, and it is love at first sight for him. During that visit, he mixes his book with Bobby's, so he goes to meet her at the library to exchange the books, and from that, both start their friendship. Raj and Bobby decide to go to see a movie but find out it is a full house. Then Raj gets an idea to go to a party. At the party, Bobby sees Raj talking to Nima (played by [[Aruna Irani]]) privately and thinks he is in love with her. As the story progresses, Raj realises that his relationship with the daughter of a poor fisherman is not taken kindly by his eccentric father. Upon Raj's insistence, Mr. Nath invites Jack Braganza to initiate talks of Raj and Bobby's wedding. But instead, Mr. Nath insults him and accuses Jack of using his daughter's beauty and charm to trap Raj for his money. He later offers Jack cash to stop Bobby from seeing Raj. Jack feels highly humiliated by this accusation and reciprocates by insulting Mr. Nath. Their talk enters a deadlock and spells doom for Raj and Bobby's tender love.\n\nMr. Nath engages Raj to a mentally challenged wealthy girl, Alka ([[Farida Jalal]]), to establish business ties with her rich father. But Raj runs away from home in order to unite with Bobby. They run away together. Mr. Nath advertises a reward for anyone who can help find his son. Prem Chopra ([[Prem Chopra]]) decides that he wants the money, and he and his goons kidnap Raj and Bobby. When they try to escape, Prem starts beating Raj. Mr. Nath and the police come to help, and they find Jack already there attempting to help Raj. Raj and Bobby run away from their fathers and jump over a waterfall. Mr. Nath and Jack jump into the water after them. Mr. Nath rescues Bobby, while Jack rescues Raj.\n\nThey realise that they love their children very much and don't want to stand in the way of their happiness. They accept each other's kids as their own and give their blessings to the union.\n\n== Cast ==\n* [[Rishi Kapoor]] as Raj Nath\n* [[Dimple Kapadia]] as Bobby Braganza\n* [[Prem Nath]] as Jack Braganza\n* [[Durga Khote]] as Mrs. Braganza\n* [[Pran (actor)|Pran]] as Mr. Nath\n* [[Sonia Sahni]] as Mrs. Sushma Nath\n* [[Aruna Irani]] as Nima\n* [[Prem Chopra]] as Prem Chopra\n* [[Farida Jalal]] as Alka 'Nikki' Sharma\n* [[Pinchoo Kapoor]] as Mr. Sharma\n* Raj Rani as Mrs. Sharma\n* [[Jagdish Raj]] as Police Inspector\n* [[Shashi Kiran]] as Shyam (Raj's college-mate)\n* [[Piloo J. Wadia]] as Mrs. Pestonji\n\n[[Raj Kapoor]] launched his second son [[Rishi Kapoor]] in this film; he wanted a new heroine to complement the young love story. [[Dimple Kapadia]] and [[Neetu Singh]] were auditioned for the role of Bobby Braganza, but Dimple was finally selected; meanwhile, Rishi Kapoor and Neetu Singh did many films together later on and became one of cinema's best screen couples and later crowned their relationship with marriage.\n\n==Production==\nIn an interview in 2012, [[Rishi Kapoor]] stated, \"There was a misconception that the film was made to launch me as an actor. The film was actually made to pay the debts of ''[[Mera Naam Joker]]''. Dad wanted to make a teenage love story and he did not have money to cast [[Rajesh Khanna]] in the film\".<ref name=\"dnaindia.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.dnaindia.com/entertainment/report_proud-of-ranbir-s-choice-of-roles-rishi-kapoor_1741229|title=Proud of Ranbir's choice of roles: Rishi Kapoor - Latest News & Updates at Daily News & Analysis|date=15 September 2012|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n===Filming===\nSome scenes were shot in [[Gulmarg]]. One scene was shot in a hut in Gulmarg, which became famous as the 'Bobby Hut'.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://movies.ndtv.com/bollywood/shah-rukh-khan-ek-kamre-mein-band-in-kashmir-262823 |title=Shah Rukh Khan ek kamre mein band in Kashmir |access-date=28 February 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140404062106/http://movies.ndtv.com/bollywood/shah-rukh-khan-ek-kamre-mein-band-in-kashmir-262823 |archive-date=4 April 2014 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>[http://www.kashmirfirst.com/articles/tourism/110301-the-gulmarg-nostalgia-10.htm The Gulmarg Nostalgia-X (Bollywood in Gulmarg-II!)]</ref> A few scenes towards the end of the movie were shot on Pune-Solapur highway near [[Loni Kalbhor]] where Raj Kapoor owned a farm.\n==Russia success==\nIt released in [[Russia|Russian Federation]] in 1975. It created amaze in [[Russian cinema]].\n\n==[[Russia|Russian Federation]] success==\nIt created havoc in [[Russian cinema]]. So it was released in Russia as a result in 1975 in [[Russian language|Russian]] and [[English language|English]]. It was one of most successful foreign films produced in Russian Federation\n\n== Soundtrack ==\nMusic by was composed by the [[Laxmikant\u2013Pyarelal|Laxmikant-Pyarelal]] Duo.The Lyrics were Penned by [[Anand Bakshi]], [[Rajkavi Inderjeet Singh Tulsi|Inderjeet Singh Tulsi]], and [[Vithalbhai Patel (lyricist)|Vithalbhai Patel]]. Lyrics penned by Anand Bakshi except where noted...Music became an evergreen hit.\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|- style=\"background:#ccc; text-align:center;\"\n! Song !! Singer(s)!! Notes\n|-\n|\"Ae Ae Ae Phansa\"\n|[[Lata Mangeshkar]]\n|Picturized on [[Aruna Irani]]\n|-\n|\"Ankhiyon Ko Rahne De\"\n|[[Lata Mangeshkar]]\n|Based on the song \"Ankhiyan nu rehen de\" by [[Reshma]]{{citation needed|reason=Your explanation here|date=February 2015}}\n|-\n|\"Beshak Mandir Masjid\"\n|[[Narendra Chanchal]]\nLyrics by Raj Kavi Inderjeet Singh Tulsi\n|\n|-\n|\"Hum Tum Ek Kamre Mein Band Ho\"\n|[[Lata Mangeshkar]] and [[Shailendra Singh (singer)|Shailendra Singh]]\n|\n|-\n|\"Jhoot Bole Kauva Kate\"\n|[[Lata Mangeshkar]] and Shailendra Singh\n|Picturized on [[Rishi Kapoor]] and [[Dimple Kapadia]] in a village dance setting.\n|-\n|\"Main Shayar To Nahin\"\n|Shailendra Singh\n|Picturised on Rishi Kapoor. The song was reused and picturised again on him in the 2004 film ''[[Hum Tum]]''.\n|-\n|\"Mujhe Kuchh Kahna Hai\"\n|[[Lata Mangeshkar]] and Shailendra Singh\n|\n|-\n|\"Na Mangun Sona Chandi\"\n|[[Manna Dey]] and Shailendra Singh\nLyrics by :Vithalbhai Patel\n|\n|}\n\n== Box office ==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"  style=\"float:right; width:45%; text-align:center;\"\n|+ Worldwide gross ({{estimation}})\n|-\n! Territory\n! Gross revenue\n! Adjusted gross\n! Footfalls\n|-\n| [[List of highest-grossing films in India|Domestic (India)]]\n| {{INR|11 [[crore]]|link=yes}}<ref name=\"boi73\"/> ({{US$|14.21 million|link=yes}}){{#tag:ref|7.742 [[Indian rupee]]s per [[US dollar]] in 1973<ref>http://fx.sauder.ubc.ca/etc/USDpages.pdf#page=3</ref>|group=n}}\n| [[Bollywood 100 Crore Club|{{INRConvert|{{Inflation|IN|398|2011}}|c}}]]{{#tag:ref|{{INR}}398 crore in 2011<ref name=\"gold70s\"/><ref name=\"gold3\"/>}}\n| {{#expr:110/(1.84*0.71+2.59*0.29) round 1}}{{nbsp}}million<ref name=\"mittal\">{{cite book |last1=Mittal |first1=Ashok |title=Cinema Industry in India: Pricing and Taxation |date=1995 |publisher=Indus Publishing |isbn=9788173870231 |pages=71 & 77 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=RJVodLc6NgoC&pg=PA77}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[List of highest-grossing Indian films in overseas markets|Overseas]] ([[List of Soviet films of the year by ticket sales|Soviet Union]])\n| 15.65{{nbsp}}million [[Soviet ruble|\u0440\u0443\u0431]]{{#tag:ref|62.6 million tickets sold,<ref name=\"soviet\"/> average ticket price of 25 [[Soviet ruble|kopecks]]<ref>[https://is.muni.cz/el/1421/podzim2015/FAV291/um/Roth-Ey-Moscow_Prime_Time.pdf#page=7 ''Moscow Prime Time: How the Soviet Union Built the Media Empire that Lost the Cultural Cold War'', page 48], [[Cornell University Press]], 2011</ref>|group=n}} {{ndash}} US$21.44{{nbsp}}million{{#tag:ref|0.73 [[Soviet ruble]]s per US dollar in 1975<ref>Archive of Bank of Russia http://cbr.ru/currency_base/OldDataFiles/USD.xls</ref>|group=n|name=RubleUSD}} ({{INR}}19.24{{nbsp}}crore){{#tag:ref|8.973 Indian rupees per US dollar in 1975<ref>https://www.rbi.org.in/scripts/PublicationsView.aspx?id=15268</ref>|group=n}}\n| US${{Inflation|US|21.44|1975}}{{nbsp}}million ({{INR}}638{{nbsp}}crore)<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.ofx.com/en-gb/forex-news/historical-exchange-rates/yearly-average-rates/ |title=67.175856 INR per USD in 2016 |access-date=18 June 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170713183556/https://www.ofx.com/en-gb/forex-news/historical-exchange-rates/yearly-average-rates/ |archive-date=13 July 2017 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n| 62.6{{nbsp}}million<ref name=\"soviet\"/>\n|-\n! [[List of highest-grossing Indian films|Worldwide]]\n! {{INR|{{#expr:11+19.24}} crore}} ({{US$|{{#expr:300/7.74 round 0}} million}})<ref name=\"hindustantimes\">{{cite news |title=On Independence Day, here are the most successful Indian movies of every decade since 1947 |url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/bollywood/on-independence-day-here-are-the-most-successful-indian-movies-of-every-decade-since-1947/story-EIf9tdhbWfO38hftOSwQIM.html |work=[[Hindustan Times]] |date=15 August 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Official exchange rate (LCU per US$, period average) |url=https://data.worldbank.org/indicator/PA.NUS.FCRF?end=1973&locations=IN&start=1972 |website=[[World Bank]] |year=1973 |accessdate=13 December 2018}}</ref>\n! [[Bollywood 1000 Crore Club|{{INR|{{#expr:574+638}} crore}}]] ({{US$|{{#expr:89+95}} million}})\n! {{#expr:53.5+62.6 round 0}}{{nbsp}}million\n|}\n\nIn India, ''Bobby'' was the highest-grossing film of 1973, earning [[Indian rupee|{{INR}}]]11 [[crore]].<ref name=\"boi73\"/> It was also the second-highest-grossing film at the Indian box office in the 1970s, second only to ''[[Sholay]]'' (1975).<ref name=\"boi70s\"/> Adjusted for inflation, it grossed {{INR}}398 crore in 2011 value,<ref name=\"gold70s\">[http://boxofficeindia.co.in/worth-their-weight-in-gold-70s/ Worth Their Weight In Gold! (70's)] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171022033244/http://boxofficeindia.co.in/worth-their-weight-in-gold-70s/# |date=22 October 2017 }}, ''[[Box Office India]]'', 3 November 2011</ref> equivalent to {{INRConvert|{{Inflation|IN|398|2011}}|c}} in 2016 value. As of 2011, it is one of the top 20 highest-grossing films of all time in India.<ref name=\"gold3\">[http://boxofficeindia.co.in/top-50-film-of-last-50-years/ Top 50 Film of Last 50 Years] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111104181418/http://boxofficeindia.co.in/top-50-film-of-last-50-years/# |date=4 November 2011 }}, ''[[Box Office India]]'', 3 November 2011</ref>\n\nOverseas, ''Bobby'' was very successful in the [[Soviet Union]] when it released there in 1975, due to Raj Kapoor's popularity in the country. ''Bobby'' drew 62.6{{nbsp}}million admissions at the Soviet box office, making it the second-best-selling film on the [[List of Soviet films of the year by ticket sales|Soviet box office charts]] in 1975,<ref name=\"soviet\">[https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=cpoLAQAAMAAJ ''Indian Films in Soviet Cinemas: The Culture of Movie-going After Stalin''], page 89, [[Indiana University Press]], 2005</ref> the most popular [[Indian film]] of the 1970s, the second-biggest foreign hit of the decade,<ref name=\"soviet-foreign\">{{cite web|url=http://kinanet.livejournal.com/13882.html|title=\u0417\u0430\u0440\u0443\u0431\u0435\u0436\u043d\u044b\u0435 \u0444\u0438\u043b\u044c\u043c\u044b \u0432 \u0441\u043e\u0432\u0435\u0442\u0441\u043a\u043e\u043c \u043a\u0438\u043d\u043e\u043f\u0440\u043e\u043a\u0430\u0442\u0435|author=Sergey Kudryavtsev|author-link=Sergey Kudryavtsev (film critic)}}</ref> the sixth-biggest box office hit of the decade,<ref name=\"soviet-foreign\"/><ref name=\"soviet-domestic\">{{cite web|url=http://kinanet.livejournal.com/14172.html|title=\u041e\u0442\u0435\u0447\u0435\u0441\u0442\u0432\u0435\u043d\u043d\u044b\u0435 \u0444\u0438\u043b\u044c\u043c\u044b \u0432 \u0441\u043e\u0432\u0435\u0442\u0441\u043a\u043e\u043c \u043a\u0438\u043d\u043e\u043f\u0440\u043e\u043a\u0430\u0442\u0435|author=Sergey Kudryavtsev|author-link=Sergey Kudryavtsev (film critic)}}</ref> the second-most-viewed Indian film of all time (after Raj Kapoor's ''[[Awaara]]''), the sixth-biggest foreign hit of all time,<ref name=\"soviet-foreign\"/> and one of the top 20 biggest box office hits of all time.<ref name=\"soviet-foreign\"/><ref name=\"soviet-domestic\"/> The film's success launched Rishi Kapoor into an overnight movie star in the Soviet Union,<ref>[https://is.muni.cz/el/1421/podzim2015/FAV291/um/Roth-Ey-Moscow_Prime_Time.pdf#page=4 ''Moscow Prime Time: How the Soviet Union Built the Media Empire that Lost the Cultural Cold War'', page 43], [[Cornell University Press]], 2011</ref> much like ''Awaara'' had done for his father Raj Kapoor.\n\n== Awards ==\n;[[21st Filmfare Awards]]\n* [[Filmfare Award for Best Actor|Best Actor]] \u2013 [[Rishi Kapoor]] (He later confessed that he bought the award for \u20b9 30000)\n* [[Filmfare Award for Best Actress|Best Actress]] \u2013 [[Dimple Kapadia]] (shared with [[Jaya Bhaduri]] for ''[[Abhimaan (1973 film)|Abhimaan]]'')\n* [[Filmfare Award for Best Male Playback Singer|Best Male Playback Singer]] \u2013 [[Narendra Chanchal]] for \"Beshak Mandir Masjid\"\n* [[Filmfare Award for Best Art Direction|Best Art Direction]] \u2013 A. Rangaraj\n* [[Filmfare Award for Best Sound Design|Best Sound Design]] \u2013 Allauddin Khan Qureshi\n\n;Nominations\n* [[Filmfare Award for Best Film|Best Film]] \u2013 [[Raj Kapoor]]\n* [[Filmfare Award for Best Director|Best Director]] \u2013 Raj Kapoor\n* [[Filmfare Award for Best Supporting Actor|Best Supporting Actor]] \u2013 [[Prem Nath]]\n* [[Filmfare Award for Best Supporting Actress|Best Supporting Actress]] \u2013 [[Aruna Irani]]\n* [[Filmfare Award for Best Music Director|Best Music Director]] \u2013 [[Laxmikant Pyarelal]]\n* [[Filmfare Award for Best Lyricist|Best Lyricist]] \u2013 [[Anand Bakshi]] for \"Hum Tum Ek Kamre Mein\"\n* Best Lyricist \u2013 Anand Bakshi for \"Main Shayer To Nahin\"\n* Best Lyricist \u2013 [[Vitthalbhai Patel]] for \"Jhoot Bole Kava Kate\"\n* Best Male Playback Singer \u2013 [[Shailender Singh]] for the song \"Main Shayar to Nahin\"\n<ref>{{cite web|url=http://deep750.googlepages.com/FilmfareAwards.pdf |title=1st Filmfare Awards 1953 |publisher=Deep750.googlepages.com |date= |accessdate=2011-06-01}}</ref>\n\n; [[Bengal Film Journalists' Association Awards|BFJA]] Awards\n* Best Male Playback Singer (Hindi Section) \u2013 [[Shailender Singh]]\n* BFJA Award for Best Audiographer (Hindi Section) \u2013 Alauddin Khan Qureshi<ref>[http://www.bfjaawards.com/legacy/pastwin/197437.htm 69th & 70th Annual Hero Honda BFJA Awards 2007] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080422070342/http://www.bfjaawards.com/legacy/pastwin/197437.htm |date=22 April 2008 }}</ref>\n\n==Controversy==\nIn his 2017 autobiography ''Khullam Khulla: Rishi Kapoor Uncensored'', [[Rishi Kapoor]] revealed that he paid someone {{INRConvert|30000|year=1974}} to win him the [[Filmfare Award for Best Actor|Best Actor]] award for ''Bobby'' at the [[21st Filmfare Awards]], beating [[Amitabh Bachchan]]'s performance for ''[[Zanjeer (1973 film)|Zanjeer]]''. However, he was not certain if the person he paid actually had connections to the Filmfare committee, or if he was just a fraud.<ref>{{cite news |title=Uncensored: Rishi Kapoor reveals *exactly* why he bought an award for Bobby |url=https://www.indiatoday.in/movies/celebrities/story/rishi-kapoor-reveals-bought-award-bobby-khullam-khulla-955884-2017-01-19 |work=[[India Today]] |date=19 January 2017}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n*[[100 Crore Club]]\n*[[List of Soviet films of the year by ticket sales]]\n\n== Notes ==\n{{reflist|group=n}}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{IMDb title|title=Bobby}}\n* {{AllRovi movie|title=Bobby}}\n* {{Rotten-tomatoes|1128675_bobby|title=Bobby}}\n\n{{Raj Kapoor}}\n{{K. A. Abbas}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bobby (1973 Film)}}\n[[Category:1973 films]]\n[[Category:1970s Hindi-language films]]\n[[Category:Urdu-language films]]\n[[Category:Indian films]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Raj Kapoor]]\n[[Category:Indian romantic musical films]]\n[[Category:1970s romantic musical films]]\n[[Category:Indian teen films]]\